'''Valence''' ({{IPA-fr|va.l<U+0251><U+0303>s}}; [[Occitan language|Occitan]]: ''Valen<U+00E7>a'') is a [[Communes of France|commune]] in southeastern France, the capital of the [[Dr<U+00F4>me]] [[Departments of France|department]] and within the [[Rh<U+00F4>ne-Alpes]] [[Regions of France|region]]. It is situated on the left bank of the [[Rh<U+00F4>ne River|Rh<U+00F4>ne]], about {{convert|100|km|mi}} south of [[Lyon]], along the railway line that runs from Paris to [[Marseilles]].

It is the 5th largest city in the region by its population, with 62,481 registered inhabitants in 2012 (127,559 inhabitants in the {{Interlanguage link|fr|Unit<U+00E9> urbaine de Valence|Unit<U+00E9> urbaine de Valence|agglomeration}}).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://insee.fr/fr/themes/tableau_local.asp?ref_id=POP&millesime=2011&typgeo=UU2010&typesearch=territoire&codgeo=UU2010+-+Valence+%2800651%29&territoire=OK|title=Insee - Population de l'unit<U+00E9> urbaine de Valence au recensement de 2011}}</ref> The city of Valence is divided into {{Interlanguage link|fr|List of cantons of Valence|Liste des cantons de Valence|four cantons}}. Its [[Demonym|inhabitants are called]] ''Valentinois''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.habitants.fr/habitants_valence_26362.html|title=Nom des habitants des communes fran<U+00E7>aises|author=David Malescourt|work=le site habitants.fr de la soci<U+00E9>t<U+00E9> commerciale Patagos}}</ref>

Located in the heart of the {{Interlanguage link|fr|Vall<U+00E9>e du Rh<U+00F4>ne (France)|Vall<U+00E9>e du Rh<U+00F4>ne (France)|Rhone corridor}}, Valence is often referred to as "the door to the [[Southern France|South of France]]", the local saying ''<U+00E0> Valence [[Southern France|le Midi]] commence'' ("at Valence the Midi begins")<!--unnecessary to cite quoted by H.C. Darby in ''The New Cambridge Modern History'' vol. ! 1957:23--> pays tribute to the city's southern culture. Between [[Vercors Massif|Vercors]] and [[Provence]], its geographical location attracts many tourists. Axes of transport and communications are the [[A7 autoroute|A7]] and [[A49 autoroute|A49]] autoroutes, the [[Route nationale 7|RN7]], [[Paris<U+2013>Marseille railway|Paris/Marseille TGV line]], as well as the [[Rh<U+00F4>ne]]. In addition, the Valence agglomeration is equipped with a {{Interlanguage link|fr|Port de l'<U+00C9>pervi<U+00E8>re|Port de l'<U+00C9>pervi<U+00E8>re|marina}}, a {{Interlanguage link|fr|Port fluvial de commerce de la Dr<U+00F4>me|Port fluvial de commerce de la Dr<U+00F4>me|trading port}}, two railway stations ([[Gare de Valence-Ville|Valence-Ville]] and [[Gare de Valence TGV|Valence-TGV]]) and an [[Valence-Chabeuil Airport|airport]]. Its business is essentially turned towards the sectors of [[Agribusiness|agriculture]], [[metallurgy]], [[Design engineer|engineering]] and [[electronics]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lexpress.fr/informations/economie-quand-valence-rime-avec-croissance_651920.html/|title=L'Express : Quand Valence rime avec croissance}}</ref>

The commune, founded in 121 BC, after the invasion of [[Gallia Narbonensis]] by the [[Roman Empire|Romans]], it moved quickly to become the largest crossroads of routes behind [[Lyon]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.museedevalence.fr/fr/musee/le-territoire|title=Mus<U+00E9>e de Valence : histoire}}</ref> With its growing importance, Valence gained the status of Roman colony. Over the centuries, the town grew and grew. Today, many vestiges of the [[Middle Ages]], [[The Renaissance|Renaissance]], but also from the 17th century, 18th century and 19th century are visible in the city centre. The city is historically attached to the [[Dauphin<U+00E9>]], of which it forms the second largest city after [[Grenoble]] and is today part of the network of [[French Towns and Lands of Art and History]]. Formerly the duchy of Valentinois, it was ruled by the [[Duke of Valentinois]], a title which is still claimed by the [[Sovereign Prince of Monaco]], though he has no actual administrative control over the area.

Valence has beautiful monuments such as the {{Interlanguage link|fr|Maison des T<U+00EA>tes de Valence|Maison des T<U+00EA>tes de Valence|Maison des T<U+00EA>tes}}, built between 1528 and 1532 by Antoine de Dorne, the [[Valence Cathedral|Saint-Apollinaire Cathedral]], built between 1063 and 1099 under the leadership of Bishop Gontard and also the {{Interlanguage link|fr|Fontaine monumentale|Fontaine monumentale|monumental fountain}} designed by the architect Eug<U+00E8>ne Poitoux. The city has many {{Interlanguage link|fr|List of historic monuments of Valence|Liste des monuments historiques de Valence|historical monuments}}, most of which are in {{Interlanguage link|fr|Vieux Valence}}. Inscribed on the list of flowery towns and villages of France, Valence is one of the seventeen municipalities of the Rh<U+00F4>ne-Alpes region to be labeled "four flowers" by the {{Interlanguage link|fr|Concours des villes et villages fleuris|Concours des villes et villages fleuris|''Concours des villes et villages fleuris''}}, i.e. the maximum level.

==Geography==

===Location===
{{main|{{Interlanguage link|fr|Vall<U+00E9>e du Rh<U+00F4>ne (France)|Vall<U+00E9>e du Rh<U+00F4>ne (France)}}|Valentinois}}

[[File:Map commune FR insee code 26362.png|thumb|left|Valence and the communes of its agglomeration]]

By its geographical location, Valence is one of the points of compulsory passage between [[Paris]] and the [[Mediterranean Sea]]. Its position at the centre of the meridian axis of the {{Interlanguage link|fr|Vall<U+00E9>e du Rh<U+00F4>ne (France)|Vall<U+00E9>e du Rh<U+00F4>ne (France)|Rhone Valley}} places the city at the mouth of the Valley of the [[Is<U+00E8>re (river)|Is<U+00E8>re]] (path to the [[Alps]]), in the west of the historical province of [[Dauphin<U+00E9>]], within the natural and historic region of the [[Valentinois]], and the boundary of the department of [[Ard<U+00E8>che]] (which it is separated by the [[Rh<U+00F4>ne]]). The city is surrounded by several mountain ranges, including the [[Massif Central]] and the Ard<U+00E8>che hills to the west, and the [[Vercors Massif]] in the [[French Prealps]] to the east. Valence is {{convert|561|km}} to the southeast of [[Paris]], equidistant ({{convert|100|km}}) south of [[Lyon]] and southwest of [[Grenoble]], {{convert|120|km}} north of [[Avignon]], {{convert|220|km}} north of [[Marseille]], {{convert|204|km}} north of [[Montpellier]], {{convert|110|km}} south-west of [[Saint-<U+00C9>tienne]], {{convert|113|km}} to the east of [[Le Puy-en-Velay]], {{convert|50|km}} north of [[Mont<U+00E9>limar]], {{convert|40|km}} to the east of [[Privas]] and {{convert|65|km}} to the west of [[Die, Dr<U+00F4>me|Die]]. Located a few kilometres south of the [[45th parallel north|45th parallel]], the city is often referred to as the "gateway to [[Southern France]]." ''"<U+00C0> Valence le Midi commence"'' [To Valence the Midi commences], say people from the north.

[[File:P1280096 - Valence.JPG|thumb|right|An aerial view of Valence]]
The agglomeration is based on four alluvial terraces ranging on the left bank of the Rhone:

*The lowest, which is closest to the river, where the districts of fishermen and sailors were.
*The intermediate terrace, safe from the floods of the river, which grew into the historic city, first within its walls, then expanded outside.
*The third terrace, highly urbanised in the second half of the 20th century.
*The highest, called the plateau of Lautagne which has developed as a centre of technological activities since the end of the 20th century on the edge of grain and vegetable farms.

Administratively, the commune is located in the south of the [[Rh<U+00F4>ne-Alpes]] region, in the northern half of the d<U+00E9>partement of [[Dr<U+00F4>me]] (of which it is the prefecture), and in the south-west of the [[Arrondissement of Valence]] (of which it is the capital). Moreover, Valence is the [[chef-lieu]] of four cantons, {{Interlanguage link|fr|Canton de Valence-1|Canton de Valence-1|Valence-1}}, {{Interlanguage link|fr|Canton de Valence-2|Canton de Valence-2|Valence-2}}, {{Interlanguage link|fr|Canton de Valence-3|Canton de Valence-3|Valence-3}} and {{Interlanguage link|fr|Canton de Valence-4|Canton de Valence-4|Valence-4}}, the city is therefore divided into four at the cantonal level . The commune is part of the {{interlanguage link|fr|Communaut<U+00E9> d'agglom<U+00E9>ration Valence-Romans Sud Rh<U+00F4>ne-Alpes}}, which includes 51 communes since its inception on 1 January 2014, and Valence is the most populous city. Valence was previously part of two intercommunalities: {{Interlanguage link|fr|Valence Agglo <U+2013> Sud Rh<U+00F4>ne-Alpes|Valence Agglo <U+2013> Sud Rh<U+00F4>ne-Alpes|SISAV}} (Intercommunal Union of Services of the Valentinoise Agglomeration, better known under the name of "Valence Major") which includes seven Dr<U+00F4>me and Ard<U+00E8>che communes (Bourg-l<U+00E8>s-Valence, Cornas, Guilherand-Granges, Portes-l<U+00E8>s-Valence, Saint-Marcel-l<U+00E8>s-Valence, Saint-P<U+00E9>ray and Valence) from 1990 to 2009, and of the agglomeration community of {{Interlanguage link|fr|Valence Agglo <U+2013> Sud Rh<U+00F4>ne-Alpes}} which consisted of eleven communes from 2009 to 2014.

