===Relief and geology===
[[File:Ruines du chateau de Crussol depuis Valence - 2014-09-27- P1940399.JPG|thumb|right|View of the ruined [[Ch<U+00E2>teau de Crussol]], in [[Ard<U+00E8>che]], seen from the {{Interlanguage link|fr|Champ de Mars (Valence)|Champ de Mars (Valence)|esplanade of the Champ de Mars}}.]]

The area of the commune is {{convert|3669|ha|acre}}, representing {{convert|36.69|km2}}; the altitude varies between {{convert|106-191|m}}.<ref>[[Institut g<U+00E9>ographique national]], ''R<U+00E9>pertoire g<U+00E9>ographique des communes'', {{cite web|url=http://professionnels.ign.fr/rgc#tab-3|title=RGC<U+00AE> <U+00E9>dition 2014}}.</ref>

The granitic base, cut by the Rh<U+00F4>ne in the Saint-Vallier/Tain-l'Hermitage pass, is covered by {{convert|4000|m|ft}} of sediments in the Valence trough. In the [[Miocene]], a [[molasse]] formed of detrital rocks due to the erosion of the [[French Alps|Alps]] and the [[Massif Central]], was deposited in a shallow sea. Its thickness can reach {{convert|400-500|m}}. During the [[Pliocene]], the sea was reduced into a lake, resulting in lacustrine deposits and [[loess]] formation. During the [[Quaternary]], between glacial periods, [[moraine]]s were swept away by the meltwater in the interglacial stages and were carved by the rivers. Thus, nested terraces were formed. These nested terraces of Is<U+00E8>re and Rh<U+00F4>ne eventually filled the gap of Valence.

The Dr<U+00F4>me des Collines, which integrates Valence, formed at the end of the Miocene. Under the effect of the Alpine thrust, the area was covered by a lake and fluvio-lacustrine molasse formed with a few ripples in the plain of Valence. The confluence of the Is<U+00E8>re and Rh<U+00F4>ne and [[fluvial]] erosion caused by their waters, in the Quaternary, formed four superimposed terraces which are located in Valence.

===Hydrography===
Valence is watered by the [[Rh<U+00F4>ne]] river, the commune is on the left bank. One of its tributaries also crosses the city: The {{Interlanguage link|fr|<U+00C9>pervi<U+00E8>re (rivi<U+00E8>re)|<U+00C9>pervi<U+00E8>re (rivi<U+00E8>re)|<U+00C9>pervi<U+00E8>re}}, a {{convert|2.6|km}}-long river,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://services.sandre.eaufrance.fr/Courdo/Fiche/client/fiche_courdo.php?CdSandre=V4011060|title=l'<U+00E9>pervi<U+00E8>re sur le site du SANDRE}}</ref> formed by the joining of most of the city's channels, among others.

===Plain of Valence===
[[File:Unit<U+00E9>s de paysage du Valentinois.JPG|thumb|left|Landscape units of [[Valentinois]]]]

The city gave its name to a well-defined geographical region: The [[Valentinois]]. Over more than three-quarters of its territory, this region corresponds to the plain of Valence, shaped by successive beds of the [[Rh<U+00F4>ne]] which are abandoned fertile sedimentary deposits. Indeed, this plain, perfectly bounded by the {{Interlanguage link|fr|Vall<U+00E9>e du Rh<U+00F4>ne (France)|Vall<U+00E9>e du Rh<U+00F4>ne (France)|Rh<U+00F4>ne Valleys}} to the west, the [[Is<U+00E8>re (river)|Is<U+00E8>re]] in the north, and the [[Dr<U+00F4>me (river)|Drome]] to the south, gives the appearance of a cheerful orchard with [[peach]], [[Prunus armeniaca|apricot]] and [[cherry]] trees, alternating with cereal and vegetable crops. Large farms, conquered one by one by the inhabitants of Valence, punctuate this agricultural area, barely broken by rivers and canals for irrigation, with groves and woods on its margins.

To the east, the Monts du Matin extend as a long barrier of pleasant hills, dominated by the limestone prow of the Vercors. To the south, beyond the Dr<U+00F4>me Valley, the plain ends at the foot of the massif carrying the vast forest of [[Marsanne, Dr<U+00F4>me|Marsanne]], topped by wind turbines.

To the north, beyond the Is<U+00E8>re Valley, the Romanais continues, geologically, Valence plain. The lower [[Miocene]] molasse in the north of the plain was covered by outwash [[alluvium]] of the Is<U+00E8>re, whose terraces today still mark the shape of the Valentinois.

The view from the ruins of the [[Ch<U+00E2>teau de Crussol]], in front after the first sharp turns in the road on leaving the {{Interlanguage link|fr|Col des Limouches}}, the plain of Valence appears as it is, a large flat surface, bordered by two reliefs which are unobscured. It is also a very large area because the of the same formation of physical organisation, one of successive terraces. Only the habitat and crops bring variation, due to the different nature of these terraces.

Today the plain of Valence is organised around the Valence infrastructure whose urban sprawl gradually extends across its whole area. A number of communes however retain their village identity and their rural character, protecting them from changing into dormitory towns. These are ancient agricultural villages, especially those that precede the first villages on the side of [[Vercors Massif|Vercors]]. Their names evoke an initial high placement to readily give a defensive view of the plain of Valence: [[Mont<U+00E9>lier]], [[Montvendre]], [[Mont<U+00E9>l<U+00E9>ger]], [[Montoison]], [[Montmeyran]] and [[Beaumont-l<U+00E8>s-Valence]].

However, the territories corresponding to the plain of Valence and the Valentinois do not include west of the agglomeration, which is located in the neighbouring department of Ard<U+00E8>che.

===Climate===
[[File:Temp<U+00E9>ratures et pr<U+00E9>cipitations en Valentinois.JPG|thumb|right|Temperature and rainfall curves of Valence in 1990]]

Valence enjoys a [[temperate climate]], whose main characteristic is an almost constant wind which blows and dries the Rh<U+00F4>ne corridor. Dubbed the "[[Mistral (wind)|mistral]]" when it comes from the north, it brings good weather and coolness in the summer, but an impression of freezing cold in winter. When it comes from the south, it usually announces the arrival of stormy disturbances. It is then called ''le vent du midi ou le vent des fous'' [the midi wind or the uncaring wind] because, for some people, it makes the atmosphere painful to bear, especially in the summer.

The climate is semi-continental with [[Mediterranean climate|Mediterranean]] influences. The Gotheron weather station of [[Saint-Marcel-l<U+00E8>s-Valence]], located {{convert|6|km}} from the centre of Valence, recorded an average temperature of 12.3&nbsp;<U+00B0>C and {{convert|886|mm|in}} of precipitation over the period from 1966 to 2004. The annual sunshine in Valence is 2,500 hours/year (average 1970-1994). However, there are large variations from one year to another, depending on the dominant influence (in turn Mediterranean and semi-continental). During the period from 1994 to 2004, the following years were remarkable: Lack of sunshine in 1996 (1,712 hours), low precipitation ({{convert|572|mm|in}}) and high temperatures in 1997, significant rainfall in 1999 ({{convert|1049|mm|in}}) and in 2002 ({{convert|1257|mm|in}}). There was significant sunshine (approx. 2,500 hours) from 1999 to 2002, accompanied by higher than average temperatures. Frost in April 2003 which affected peach production, follwed by a summer heatwave in 2003, with exceptional sunshine for the year (2,781 hours), and a rainfall deficit in 2004 ({{convert|722|mm|in}}).<ref>{{cite web | url = http://orgprints.org/7699/1/AB_INRA_Gotheron_2006.pdf | title = Arboriculture biologique : 11 ann<U+00E9>es d<U+2019>exp<U+00E9>rimentation en vergers de p<U+00EA>chers et pommiers - R<U+00E9>sultats exp<U+00E9>rimentaux 1994-2004, Suivi longitudinal, Impact du mode de production |language=fr|trans-title=Organic Arboriculture : 11 years of experimentation in peach orchards and apple - Experimental Results 1994-2004 Longitudinal follow-up , mode of production Impact| publisher = INRA Gotheron, in partnership with Agribiodr<U+00F4>me and GRAB | date = March 2006}}</ref>

Valence is located in the Rh<U+00F4>ne Valley where the wind regime is regular, both from the south (mistral) and north. Adding in the course of the Rh<U+00F4>ne which is linear from Lyon to Valence, this circumstance has allowed navigable sailing on the Rh<U+00F4>ne from Valence.<ref>{{cite book|first=M.|last=Rossiaud|url=http://www.persee.fr/web/revues/home/prescript/article/shmes_1261-9078_1978_act_7_1_1239|title=Les haleurs du Rh<U+00F4>ne au XVe siecle|work=Actes des congr<U+00E8>s de la Soci<U+00E9>t<U+00E9> des historiens m<U+00E9>di<U+00E9>vistes de l'enseignement sup<U+00E9>rieur public, 7e congr<U+00E8>s|location=Rennes|year=1976|id=Les transports au Moyen <U+00C2>ge|page=286}}</ref>

===Vegetation===
The vegetation in the plain of Valence is mid-European with a supra-Mediterranean floor ([[Quercus robur|pedunculate oak]], oak found in the coldest places, and thickets of [[hornbeam]]) mingled with thermophilic species such as [[Quercus pubescens|downy oak]], or even [[Quercus ilex|evergreen oaks]] on exposed slopes with draining soils. Found also in the south of the Dr<U+00F4>me Valley where the Mediterranean influence finally prevails ({{convert|20|km}} to the South) are spontaneous populations of [[Thymus (plant)|thyme]], [[Lavandula|lavender]], [[Euphorbia characias]], Spanish broom ({{interlanguage link|fr|Genista hispanica}}), cane of Provence ([[Arundo donax]]), as well as [[Pinus halepensis|Aleppo pines]] on the western face of the massif of [[Ch<U+00E2>teau de Crussol|Crussol]]. Due to the exposure and the nature of the soil, the Ard<U+00E8>che hills offer landscapes of [[garrigue]] and Mediterranean Oak (Quercus Ilex) from [[Tournon-sur-Rh<U+00F4>ne|Tournon]] which is located {{convert|22|km}} north of Valence (hills of [[Cornas]], [[Ch<U+00E2>teau de Crussol]] and [[Soyons]]). The hills (mostly limestone) have a double vegetation: Mediterranean on the southern side and Sub-continental on the northern side.

Formerly, the cultivation of olive trees was previously on the well-exposed heights of Tain-l'Hermitage ({{convert|19|km}} to the north), but they were replaced by the culture of the vine at first, and then by that of apricot, peach and other fruit which are still very present in the region, even though more than {{convert|7000|ha|acre}} of fruit (mainly apricots, cherries, peaches and kiwis) disappeared from the Dr<U+00F4>me landscapes due to an outbreak of [[Plum pox|sharka]] and a [[Pathogenic bacteria|bacterial infection]] forcing wilt since 2003.

==Communication and transport==
The central railway station of Valence is the [[Gare de Valence-Ville]], located just south of the town centre. The station offers connections to Lyon, Grenoble, Avignon, Gap and several regional destinations. In 2001 the [[Gare de Valence TGV]] opened along with the [[LGV M<U+00E9>diterran<U+00E9>e]], a [[high-speed rail]] line extending south from Valence to [[Marseilles]]. The station is only {{Convert|1|km|mi|0}} south of the end of the [[LGV Rh<U+00F4>ne-Alpes]], giving Valence much shorter journey times to northern destinations as well, with a journey to Paris taking 2h11. The TGV station is located 10&nbsp;km northeast of the town.

A [[Bicycle sharing system|bikesharing]] scheme called Lib<U+00E9>lo started in March 2010, offering 200 bicycles for long-term hire and 180 for short-term hire, in 18 locations around the city. Charges are collected by smart card or credit card.<ref>{{Cite web
 |url= http://velo-libelo.fr/ |title=Lib<U+00E9>lo, le service v<U+00E9>lo de VALENCE AGGLO Sud Rh<U+00F4>ne-Alpes, Guilherand-Granges, Saint-P<U+00E9>ray, Cornas |language=French
 |work=velo-libelo.fr  |accessdate=2 October 2010}}</ref>

===Road network===
[[File:L'autouroute A7 <U+00E0> Valence.JPG|thumb|right||The A7 at the northern entrance to Valence, looking southbound.]]

The city occupies a key position, at the centre of the {{Interlanguage link|fr|Rh<U+00F4>ne Valley (France)|Vall<U+00E9>e du Rh<U+00F4>ne (France)|Rh<U+00F4>ne Valley}}. Located on a crossroads of road networks, it is known to be a point of passage (cf. the Valence Autoroute Area) of the holidaymakers who head to the C<U+00F4>te d'Azur. The [[A7 autoroute]] (commonly known as the ''autoroute du soleil'' [motorway of the sun]) connects it to [[Lyon]] ({{convert|100|km}} to the north), [[Avignon]] ({{convert|120|km}} to the south), then to [[Marseille]] ({{convert|220|km}} south). The [[A49 autoroute]] connects it to [[Grenoble]] ({{convert|95|km}} to the northeast). The [[A41 autoroute]] connects it to [[Savoy]] ([[Chamb<U+00E9>ry]] and [[Annecy]]; {{convert|158|km}} and {{convert|206|km}} respectively) and [[Geneva]] (Switzerland) {{convert|245|km}} to the northeast (via the A49).

On the other hand, relations with the cities of the [[Massif Central]] ([[Le Puy-en-Velay]] and [[Clermont-Ferrand]]) are more difficult as the roads are very winding. For example, the shortest route to reach [[Saint-<U+00C9>tienne]] passes through the [[Col de la R<U+00E9>publique]] (ex-{{Interlanguage link|fr|Route nationale 82 (France)|Route nationale 82 (France)|RN 82}}) at {{convert|1161|m}} altitude.

====Underground project of the A7====
In Valence, the [[A7 autoroute]] runs along the [[Rh<U+00F4>ne]] and thus crosses the city by cutting the river. An underground project of the autoroute up to the city is being studied.<ref name="point2011">{{cite web|url=http://www.lepoint.fr/.../une-ville-en-devenir-10-03-2011-1307671_27.php/|title=Le Point : Une ville en devenir}}</ref>

The city of Valence was cut off from its river during the construction of the A7 motorway in the 1960s. The idea is born to bury the fast axis semi-covered trenches over a distance of about {{convert|1.5|km}}. This project to bury the motorway should make the banks of the Rh<U+00F4>ne available to Valence. However, the project would not be completed prior to at least 2025. The studies, which will be soon carried out, should enable a decision on the exact length of motorway involved, the technical choices and the financial cost. According to a preliminary study, the construction costs should culminate in an amount of <U+20AC>500 million, of which the cost will be shared between the State, the company {{Interlanguage link|fr|Vinci Autoroutes}}, the department of Dr<U+00F4>me and the city of Valence.

====Valence ring road====
The p<U+00E9>riph<U+00E9>rique ([[ring road]]) of Valence consists of the A7 autoroute, [[Route nationale 7]] and the {{Interlanguage link|fr|Route nationale 532}}. It is located on the European routes [[European route E15|E15]] (A7) and [[European route E713|E713]] (RN 532).

Forming a half-loop, the Valence ring road covers a little more than {{convert|22|km}} and connects the commune of [[Bourg-l<U+00E8>s-Valence]] to the north (up to the toll of Valence Nord) in the city quarter of {{Interlanguage link|fr|Fontlozier}} to the south (to the toll of Valence Sud exit), thus bypassing the major part of the city whilst ensuring the city is served to the east. It also allows easy access to the [[Gare de Valence TGV|Valence TGV station]] in the north, by the {{Interlanguage link|fr|Route nationale 532|Route nationale 532|RN 532}}. The ring road of Valence features motorway except in two singular points. The portion of the [[A7 autoroute]] in the centre is the legacy of the 1960s when the city turned back to its river. It is even doubled by urban roads, the D2007N.

Plans to form a complete loop, connecting the current ring road to a western bypass of Valence, on the right bank of the [[Rh<U+00F4>ne]], are under consideration. The east ring road is of more recent design and it ensures the continuity of the RN 7, which offers a free alternative to the A7. This section also provides the extension of the [[A49 autoroute]] right to Valence. A road-doubling project of the A7 and A49 autoroutes was considered to relieve the ring road of its transit traffic but was abandoned, even though this axis was granted to the society of the {{Interlanguage link|fr|Autoroutes du Sud de la France}} (ASF) and acquisitions had been completed.

The west bypass is gradually emerging and it relates directly to the department of [[Ard<U+00E8>che]]. It is materialised by a second bridge (L<U+00F4>nes Bridge) on the Rh<U+00F4>ne (D 96 and D 534) coming to relieve the Mistral Bridge located in the city centre. This bypass is to develop because it is located in the core trunk with the D86, the main axis of the right bank of the Rh<U+00F4>ne. The bypass of the communes of [[Guilherand-Granges]], [[Saint-P<U+00E9>ray]] and [[Cornas]] is programmed, which ensures its realisation by 2025. It will then require the construction of a third bridge over the Rh<U+00F4>ne in the north of the metropolitan area (in Bourg-l<U+00E8>s-Valence) to complete the ring road that will then form a complete loop: This project is at the stage of preliminary studies and it seems that a passage on the present dam of the [[Compagnie Nationale du Rh<U+00F4>ne|CNR]] is retained in order to minimise the cost.

===The bridges of Valence===
[[File:Valence pont cpa ll.jpg|thumb|right|The former stone bridge (around 1919), replaced in 1967 by the Fr<U+00E9>d<U+00E9>ric-Mistral Bridge.]]

During antiquity, the existence of a bridge providing, as in [[Vienne, Is<U+00E8>re|Vienne]], the link between the two shores, is likely. Indeed, as early as 1388, the toponym "Pont P<U+00E9>ri" [P<U+00E9>ri Bridge] is carried by a sector of the quarter of Basse-Ville lying in the extension of the east-west axis of the ancient city. In addition, A. Blanc would have discovered, still in this same extension, piles of oak, closer perhaps to a pier. He also mentioned the "tour de Constance" [Constance Tower], on the Valence shore, a construction already known in the Middle Ages and which bore all the floods of the Rh<U+00F4>ne. In any case, the existence of a link between the two banks is in no doubt and a crossing point could even have existed at the site of Valence from the prehistoric time. Whether or not that existed, this ancient bridge was not replaced until the nineteenth century.

The different successive bridges of Valence, in chronological order, are:

*The [[Marc Seguin|Seguin]] Bridge built from 1827 (two years after that of [[Tain-l'Hermitage|Tain]]-[[Tournon-sur-Rh<U+00F4>ne|Tournon]], which was the first bridge of this type installed in France) and delivered to traffic in 1830.
*The stone bridge, dating from 1905, destroyed 19 June 1940 by French engineers to slow the advance of the German troops. In August 1940, Rhone is again passable by boat and then a ferry to traille. A temporary {{Interlanguage link|fr|Gaston Pigeaud|Gaston Pigeaud|Pigeaud}} bridge was then installed by the engineers. This bridge was again damaged on 18 August 1944 during a bombing by the Allied forces.
*A temporary suspended walkway installed in 1949 and which was in use until 1967.
*The [[Fr<U+00E9>d<U+00E9>ric Mistral]] Bridge, completed in 1967, is still in service. It joins the commune of [[Guilherand-Granges]] (Ard<U+00E8>che) to the city centre of Valence (Dr<U+00F4>me).
*Finally, the {{Interlanguage link|fr|L<U+00F4>ne|L<U+00F4>ne|L<U+00F4>nes}} Bridge was inaugurated on 18 December 2004, located at the south of the city, is the "second bridge" of Valence, long expected to alleviate the problems of movement between the two banks of the Rhone. It connects the municipalities of Guilherand-Granges and [[Soyons]] (Ard<U+00E8>che) in the southern districts of Valence.

During long periods where no bridge was available, a [[reaction ferry]] could cross the Rhone River. On the right bank, in Guilherand-Granges, an old pile used by this {{Interlanguage link|fr|bac|bac|ferry}} is still erect.

===Railway===
{{main|Gare de Valence-Ville|Gare de Valence TGV}}
[[File:Valence-Gare.jpg|thumb|left||Fa<U+00E7>ade of the gare de Valence-Ville. Statue of [[Fran<U+00E7>ois-D<U+00E9>sir<U+00E9> Bancel]].]]

Commissioned in 1865, the role of the [[gare de Valence-Ville|Valence-Ville]] railway station has refocused on regional transport since the commissioning of the [[gare de Valence TGV]] or simply Valence-TGV. It is the point of departure of the trains in the direction of [[Grenoble]], [[Chamb<U+00E9>ry]], [[Annecy]] and [[Geneva]]. Valence-Ville railway station was also the origin of the relationship which serves {{Interlanguage link|fr|Gare de Livron|Gare de Livron|Livron}}, {{Interlanguage link|fr|Gare de Crest|Gare de Crest|Crest}}, {{Interlanguage link|fr|Gare de Die|Gare de Die|Die}}, {{Interlanguage link|fr|Gare de Veynes-D<U+00E9>voluy|Gare de Veynes-D<U+00E9>voluy|Veynes-D<U+00E9>voluy}}, {{Interlanguage link|fr|Gare de Gap|Gare de Gap|Gap}}, {{Interlanguage link|fr|Gare d'Embrun|Gare d'Embrun|Embrun}} and {{Interlanguage link|fr|Gare de Brian<U+00E7>on|Gare de Brian<U+00E7>on|Brian<U+00E7>on}}. The passenger building of Valence-Ville railway station has been in service in April 1866. It was designed by {{Interlanguage link|fr|Louis-Jules Bouchot}},<ref>{{cite journal|first=Fran<U+00E7>ois|last=Pourpardin|title=Les b<U+00E2>timents voyageurs <U+00E9>difi<U+00E9>s le long de la ligne imp<U+00E9>riale (La Compagnie du PLM : les gares de l'architecte Jules Bouchot)|journal=[[Revue d'histoire des chemins de fer|Revue d<U+2019>histoire des chemins de fer]]|issue=38|year=2008|pages=59<U+2013>71|url=http://rhcf.revues.org/404}}</ref> architect of [[Napoleon III]]. The facade of the main body, in stone, is inspired by the [[Petit Trianon]] of [[Versailles]]. The main fa<U+00E7>ade on the ''Rue du Pavilion Central'' has been registered as an [[Monument historique|historic monument]] since 11 October 1982.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.culture.gouv.fr/public/mistral/merimee_fr?ACTION=CHERCHER&FIELD_1=REF&VALUE_1=PA00117088|title=Monuments historiques|accessdate=4 May 2015}}</ref>

[[File:Gare de Valence TGV-1.jpg|thumb|right|A train at the [[Gare de Valence-Rh<U+00F4>ne-Alpes-Sud TGV|Valence-TGV]] railway station]]

[[Gare de Valence TGV|Valence TGV]] railway station, on the [[LGV M<U+00E9>diterran<U+00E9>e]] line, is located {{convert|11|km}} north-east of the city centre. Before putting this station into service, the [[TGV]] stopped in Valence-Ville railway station, allowing trains to reach Paris in 2 hours 36 minutes, for example. At the opening of the TGV station in June 2001, a service of fifty TGVs per day was planned, with eight TGVs continuing to serve Valence-Ville.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.leparisien.fr/economie/le-tgv-pour-valence-plus-long-et-plus-cher-09-05-2001-2002154506.php|title=Le TGV pour Valence plus long et plus cher|work=Le Parisien|date=26 May 2001}}</ref> Valence TGV station is regularly connected to 35 cities, including [[Paris-Gare de Lyon|Paris]], [[Gare de Marseille-Saint-Charles|Marseille]], [[Gare de Lyon Saint-Exup<U+00E9>ry|Lyon]], [[Gare de Toulouse-Matabiau|Toulouse]], [[Gare de Lille Europe|Lille]], [[Gare de Nice-Ville|Nice]], [[Gare de Montpellier-Saint-Roch|Montpellier]], [[Gare de Nantes|Nantes]], [[Gare du Havre|Le Havre]], [[Gare de Reims|Reims]], [[Gare d'Avignon TGV|Avignon]], [[Gare de Besan<U+00E7>on Franche-Comt<U+00E9> TGV|Besan<U+00E7>on]], [[Gare de Strasbourg|Strasbourg]], [[Gare de Dijon-Ville|Dijon]] and [[Brussels-South railway station|Brussels]].

In 2003, 60 daily TGVs served the station, with 1.8 million passengers.<ref name="point2007">{{cite web|url=http://www.lepoint.fr/archives/article.php/34028|title=Terre des sens, sur de nouveaux rails|work=Le Point|date=17 January 2007}}</ref>

In 2008, the station was served by 58 daily TGVs, carrying 2.2 million passengers.<ref name="rovaltain.fr">{{cite web|url=http://www.rovaltain.fr/pole-economique.html|title=un P<U+00F4>le <U+00E9>conomique au sud de Lyon|language=fr|trans-title=An economic pole south of Lyon|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090708135846/http://www.rovaltain.fr/pole-economique.html|archivedate=8 July 2009}}</ref>

===Public transport===
{{main|{{Interlanguage link|fr|Public transport of Valence and Romans-sur-Is<U+00E8>re|Transports en commun de Valence et Romans-sur-Is<U+00E8>re|Cit<U+00E9>a}}}}

The region has a bus network called ''Cit<U+00E9>a'' which covers the Valence [[Urban agglomeration|agglomeration]] (located across the departments of [[Dr<U+00F4>me]] and [[Ard<U+00E8>che]]) and the [[Romans-sur-Is<U+00E8>re|romano]]-[[Bourg-de-P<U+00E9>age|peageoise]] town (about {{convert|20|km}} north of Valence). The network is managed by ''Valence Romans D<U+00E9>placements'' and controlled by the {{Interlanguage link|fr|Communaut<U+00E9> d'agglom<U+00E9>ration Valence-Romans Sud Rh<U+00F4>ne-Alpes}} and its operation is entrusted to VTV (''V<U+00E9>olia Transport Valence'') from 2012 (the former CTAV network to July 2006). Given the large extent of the Cit<U+00E9>a network, the latter is divided into two sectors, Valence and [[Romans-sur-Is<U+00E8>re]].

The territory covered by the network is {{convert|1037|km2}}. It consists of 64 communes located in and around the towns of Valence and Romans-sur-Is<U+00E8>re and is inhabited by nearly 220,000 people. Fourth urban network of the Rh<U+00F4>ne-Alpes region, it has 20 regular lines, over 200 stops and a fleet of 220 bus.

The {{Interlanguage link|fr|Carte O<U+00F9>RA!|Carte O<U+00F9>RA!|Oura! card}} is a transport document which consists of a smartcard which allows not only to travel on any Cit<U+00E9>a network (charging its transport tickets), but also to combine travel with other modes of transport in the region such as the [[TER Rh<U+00F4>ne-Alpes]] ([[Transport express r<U+00E9>gional]]), networks of transit of Saint Etienne ([[Soci<U+00E9>t<U+00E9> de Transports de l'Agglom<U+00E9>ration St<U+00E9>phanoise|STAS]]), Grenoble ({{Interlanguage link|fr|Transports de l'agglom<U+00E9>ration grenobloise|Transports de l'agglom<U+00E9>ration grenobloise|TAG}}) or Lyon ([[Transports en commun lyonnais|TCL]]), or even rent-a-bike in free service.

====Self-service bicycles====
[[File:Lib<U+00E9>lo.jpg|thumb|right|A [[Lib<U+00E9>lo]] bicycle station, in the city centre of Valence]]
{{main|Lib<U+00E9>lo}}
Since March 28, 2010, the city has a system of self-service [[Bicycle sharing system|rent-a-bike]] and long-term hire called [[Lib<U+00E9>lo]]. It includes 160 bikes on the [[Smoove]] key concept spread over 18 then 20 stations and 200 rental bikes for long duration in Valence, [[Guilherand-Granges]] and [[Bourg-l<U+00E8>s-Valence]].

Unlike most other bike sharing systems, its management is not delegated to a business, or related to an advertising market but provided by the transport company of Valence (subsidiary of [[Transdev]]) in partnership with the Cit<U+00E9>a transit network.

===Inland waterway===
{{main|{{Interlanguage link|fr|Port de l'<U+00C9>pervi<U+00E8>re}}|{{Interlanguage link|fr|Port fluvial de commerce de la Dr<U+00F4>me}}}}
The {{Interlanguage link|fr|Port de l'<U+00C9>pervi<U+00E8>re|Port de l'<U+00C9>pervi<U+00E8>re||marina of <U+00C9>pervi<U+00E8>re}} contains 478 berths: It is the first river port of [[France]]. Built in 1973, at the initiative of the {{Interlanguage link|fr|Chambre de commerce et d'industrie de la Dr<U+00F4>me|Chambre de commerce et d'industrie de la Dr<U+00F4>me|Chamber of commerce and industry of Dr<U+00F4>me}} (CCI of Dr<U+00F4>me), around a pool of {{convert|44000|m2|sqft}}, it is included in a leisure park of {{convert|17|ha|acre}}. The quality of the services offered allowed it to obtain the [[Blue Flag beach|blue flag]] of Europe, in 2005.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.drome-portdeplaisance.com/|title=port de plaisance}}</ref>

Created in 1978 and operated by the {{Interlanguage link|fr|Chambre de commerce et d'industrie de la Dr<U+00F4>me|Chambre de commerce et d'industrie de la Dr<U+00F4>me|CCI of Dr<U+00F4>me}},<ref name="portval">{{cite web|url=http://www.drome-portdecommerce.com/|title=port de commerce de la Dr<U+00F4>me}}</ref> the {{Interlanguage link|fr|Port fluvial de commerce de la Dr<U+00F4>me|Port fluvial de commerce de la Dr<U+00F4>me|river port of trade}} in the Dr<U+00F4>me (more often called Port of Valence) is located for its part, on the territory of the commune of [[Portes-l<U+00E8>s-Valence]], just to the south of the city of Valence. It spread over {{convert|41|ha|acre}} and has in addition to the port itself, an industrial zone with {{convert|9|ha|acre}} of area of warehouses, including customs, a grain terminal, a 'wood' centre, and the storage sheds ({{convert|7600|m2|sqft}} all products).<ref name="portval" /> Its strategic location on the Rh<U+00F4>ne (in the heart of the [[Rh<U+00F4>ne-Alpes]] region, close to [[Is<U+00E8>re]], [[Savoy]] and [[Switzerland]]) allows it to serve the countries of the [[Mediterranean Basin]] and the Middle East.<ref name="portval" /> As of July 2013, the [[Compagnie Nationale du Rh<U+00F4>ne]] (CNR) began a campaign of work, with a cost of <U+20AC>14 million, to develop the port to make it a place of exchange at the European level.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wk-transport-logistique.fr/actualites/detail/68067/le-port-fluvial-de-valence-lance-les-travaux-pour-developper-sa-vocation-multimodale.html|title=Travaux de la CNR}}</ref>

===Air===
{{main|Valence-Chabeuil Airport}}

{| cellpadding="2" cellspacing="0"  style="background-color: #eef5ff; text-align:center;float:right;border:thin solid #ccc;padding:0.3em;font-size:85%;"
|+'''Nearby airports'''
! style="background-color: #ddf;" | Name
! style="background-color: #ddf;" | Destinations
! style="background-color: #ddf;" | Distance
|-
|style="text-align: left;" |[[Valence-Chabeuil Airport|Valence-Chabeuil]]||''[[France]]''||{{convert|5|km}}
|-style="background:#ffe;"
|style="text-align: left;" |[[Grenoble<U+2013>Is<U+00E8>re Airport|Grenoble-Is<U+00E8>re]]||''[[Europe]]''||{{convert|80|km}}
|-
|style="text-align: left;" |[[Lyon<U+2013>Saint-Exup<U+00E9>ry Airport|Lyon-Saint-Exup<U+00E9>ry]]||''[[Europe]], [[Africa]],<br /> [[North America]]''||{{convert|114|km}}
|-style="background:#ffe;"
|}

[[Valence-Chabeuil Airport]], located in the commune of [[Chabeuil]], is co-managed by the {{Interlanguage link|fr|General Council of the Dr<U+00F4>me|Conseil d<U+00E9>partemental de la Dr<U+00F4>me}} and the Chamber of commerce and industry of Dr<U+00F4>me.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.drome.cci.fr/vous-etes/acteur-public/decouvrir/laeroport-de-valence-chabeuil/|title=A<U+00E9>roport de Valence-Chabreuil}}</ref> It is open to commercial national traffic, to private aircraft, using [[Instrument flight rules|IFR]] and [[Visual flight rules|VFR]] but welcomes more regular routes since the decision of the Valence-[[Paris]] service,{{when|date=May 2015}} which has run since 1969.

The airport has three runways: one of {{convert|2100|m|ft}} in concrete, and two smaller, {{convert|1300|m|ft}} and {{convert|440|m|ft}}. The {{convert|530|m2|sqft}} terminal has two gateways for access to aircraft. The aircraft parking area is {{convert|16000|m2|sqft}}. Passengers have at their disposal a 150-space car park and a hotel area. A flying club, as well as a helicopter company{{which|date=May 2015}} are installed at the airport.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aeroport.fr/les-aeroports-de-l-uaf/valence-chabeuil.php|title=infrastructures}}</ref>

[[Grenoble-Is<U+00E8>re Airport]] is located {{convert|80|km}} north-east of Valence along the A49 and offers flights to several European cities including Barcelona, Dublin, Rotterdam and Warsaw. [[Lyon-Saint-Exup<U+00E9>ry Airport]] is {{convert|114|km}} north of Valence via the A7 motorway and offers international flights. The airport is considered to be the second airport in the province after Nice-C<U+00F4>te d'Azur Airport and connects Lyon with most capitals and major European cities. More than 100 cities are connected one or more times a week, some up to five times per day, such as London. In 2013, the Lyon-Saint-Exup<U+00E9>ry airport processed more than 8.5 million passengers.

==Urban planning==

===Urban morphology===
The old centre is based on the Roman foundation on a [[grid plan]], occupation of the banks of the Rhone is sparse, probably because of instability.<ref>{{cite book|first1=G<U+00E9>rard|last1=Chouquer|first2=Thierry|last2=Odiot|first3=Alain|last3=Beeching|first4=Jacques L<U+00E9>opold|last4=Brochier|first5=Sylvio|last5=Matteucci|url=http://www.persee.fr/web/revues/home/prescript/article/dha_0755-7256_1984_num_10_1_1632|title=L'<U+00E9>volution morphohistorique de la cit<U+00E9> de Valence|id=Dialogues d'histoire ancienne|volume=10|year=1984|page=369}}</ref> The orientation of the streets of the Roman city, orientation still quite widespread in the streets of the old town, is identical to those of the ancient [[cadastre]]s of the surrounding countryside. The grid plan follows a dual orientation, varying neighbourhoods, the dual orientation which corresponds to two modules of this plan: One of about 360 Roman feet ({{convert|107|m}}), the other 420 feet, which sometimes breaks down into 120 feet spacing. This second module describes the angle of the ''Rue l<U+2019><U+00C9>querre'';  {{interlanguage link|fr|Place des Ormeaux}} exactly a square ''actus'' (i.e. a square with a side of 120 Roman feet); the [[Valence Cathedral|Saint-Apollinaire Cathedral]] occupies two square ''actus''.<ref name="chouquer-odiot-370">Chouquer, Odiot, opcit, p.370</ref> The presence of the Roman [[amphitheatre]] near the Porte Neuve [New Gate] is detectable only in the design of the streets of the cadastre from 1807.<ref name="chouquer-odiot-371">Chouquer, Odiot, opcit, p.371</ref>

The first alluvial terrace, at {{convert|120-125|m}} altitude, was fully occupied by the western part of the communal territory in the 1960s. The city of Valence then expanded eastward, on the [[Riss glaciation|Riss]] terrace, at an altitude of approximately {{convert|150|m}}. To the south, the Lautagne plateau, at an altitude of {{convert|180|m}}, determines a narrow groove between this advance from the terrace of la L<U+00E9>ore and the Rh<U+00F4>ne, which has limited the development of the city in that direction. At the end of the 20th century, the city was again cut off from the Rh<U+00F4>ne by the construction of the [[A7 autoroute]].<ref>{{cite journal|first1=Pierre|last1=Dubesset|url=http://www.persee.fr/web/revues/home/prescript/article/geoca_0035-113x_1974_num_49_3_1655|title=Perspectives actuelles de l'am<U+00E9>nagement urbain <U+00E0> Valence-sur-Rh<U+00F4>ne|id=Revue de g<U+00E9>ographie de Lyon|volume=49|issue=3|year=1974|page=286}}</ref> Port areas are alone in the south towards [[Portes-l<U+00E8>s-Valence]].<ref>RG 287</ref> The Valence agglomeration stretches on the right bank of the Rh<U+00F4>ne, but is limited by the edge of the Vivarais plateau. However, it includes the communes of [[Guilherand-Granges]], [[Saint-P<U+00E9>ray]], [[Cornas]] and [[Soyons]].<ref>Dubesset 1974, opcit, p.286-8</ref>

To facilitate the expansion of the town to the east, a large expressway was built (it is used by the RN7),<ref>Dubesset 1974, opcit, p.288</ref> where the [[Valence-Chabeuil Airport]] has been in operation since 1969.<ref>{{cite journal|first1=Pierre|last1=Dubesset|url=http://www.persee.fr/web/revues/home/prescript/article/geoca_0035-113x_1971_num_46_4_1597|title=L'a<U+00E9>roport de Valence-Chabeuil|id=Revue de g<U+00E9>ographie de Lyon|volume=46|issue=4|year=1971|page=449}}</ref>

===Quarters===
{{main|{{Interlanguage link|fr|Quarters of Valence|Quartiers de Valence}}}}
[[File:Vue de Valence dans la Dr<U+00F4>me depuis le plateau de Lautagne.jpg|thumb|centre|750px||View of the southern districts of Valence from the plateau of Lautagne]]

The city of Valence is made of twenty [[Quarter (urban subdivision)|quarter]]s (with an average of 3,500 people per quarter). They are all different from the other: The northern quarters are rather popular and residential (Polygone, Fontbarlettes, le Plan and la Chamberli<U+00E8>re) and even rural (Thodure), while the southern quarters are generally inhabited by the middle class and pensioners ({{Interlanguage link|fr|Fontlozier}}, Hugo-Provence, Laprat, les Baumes, Mannet, Valence Sud and Lautagne), although there is a popular district (Valensolles), the central quarters are commercial and animated (Centre-ville, Gare, Victor Hugo) and also for tourists during the summer ({{Interlanguage link|fr|Vieux Valence}}, Basse ville, l'<U+00C9>pervi<U+00E8>re) and the east quarters are areas with residential character (Baquet, Grand Charran, Petit Charran, Ch<U+00E2>teauvert, Danton and Briffaut), however the Martins quarter is rather rural.

Some districts are represented by a {{Interlanguage link|fr|Comit<U+00E9> de quartier|Comit<U+00E9> de quartier|"Quarter Committee"}}, which makes for a very lively micro-local fabric. A Quarter Committee is an association of people who play a role with regard to public institutions, and who allow an exchange of information between people and municipal services. In this way, residents can participate in the direction of development projects of their quarters according to their aspirations.

To avoid a trip to the city hall, the city of Valence has created five city hall branches in outlying quarters. The mayoral branches of Fontbarlettes, le Plan, Centre-Ville, Valence Sud and the Chamberli<U+00E8>re are placed at the disposal of the inhabitants and are in charge of certain administrative services delegated by the Central Council.

===Housing===
In 2009, the total number of dwellings in the municipality was 34,661, while it was 32,376 in 1999.<ref>''LOG T1M - <U+00C9>volution of the number of houses by category.</ref>

Among this housing, 88.4% were primary residences, 1.0% of secondary residences and 10.6% vacant housing. These dwellings were 24.1% detached houses and 74.7% of apartments.<ref name="LOG T2">''LOG T2 - Categories and types of housing.</ref>

The proportion of primary residences, as properties of their occupants, was 43.1%, up slightly from 1999 (41.1%). The share of social housing (empty rented [[HLM]]) was 16.5% against 18.8%, their number having dropped: 5,059 against 5,439.<ref>''LOG T7 - Main residences by occupancy status.</ref>

Concerning social housing, there are several organisations which are the Public Housing Office of Valence (OPH) and Housing Development of Dr<U+00F4>me (DAH) who construct, maintain and manage social housing throughout the city and in the Valence agglomeration,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dromeamenagementhabitat.fr/espace-collectivites-locales/|title=Dr<U+00F4>me Am<U+00E9>nagement Habitat (DAH)}}</ref> most are located in so-called working-class quarters. As for the grants of the OPH, they come from the city of Valence, the Dr<U+00F4>me department, the region and the State.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.drome-hebdo.fr/blog/2011/02/28/du-negatif-au-positif/|title=Dr<U+00F4>me-Hebdo : Logements sociaux <U+00E0> Valence}}</ref> Those of DAH come mainly from the department.

===Development projects===
The major projects of the municipality do not yet concern the city centre, even if they have the merit of addressing the three terraces which line the city: the first terrace concerns Valence-le-Haut (quarters of le Plan and Fontbarlettes), the second concerns the centre and the south, and the third the banks of the [[Rh<U+00F4>ne]].

One of the city's major projects is the reclamation of the banks, disfigured by the passage of the A7 motorway over {{convert|1.4|km}}.<ref name="point2011" /> When he was Mayor of Valence, Member of Parliament [[Patrick Labaune]] had defended a bypass with an eastern route. Thus advocating the "removal the A7", when elected, specifically a burial of the motorway in semi-covered trenches. The project would have been validated by the company of the {{Interlanguage link|fr|Autoroutes du Sud de la France}} (ASF), but the mayor refuses for now to give a price, which would be some <U+20AC>500 million according to experts.<ref name="point2011" /><ref name="calameo">{{cite web|url=http://www.calameo.com/books/000021831a9e850c22d0e/|title=Grands projets de ville}}</ref>

Other projects will be launched to create a {{convert|24|km}} [[Greenway (landscape)|green route]], on the banks, through the municipalities of Valence and [[Bourg-l<U+00E8>s-Valence]]. In addition to a renovation of the tourist facilities on the site of the {{Interlanguage link|fr|Port de l'<U+00C9>pervi<U+00E8>re|Port de l'<U+00C9>pervi<U+00E8>re|l'<U+00C9>pervi<U+00E8>re}}, the city wants to transform the <U+00EE>les quarter into an [[Ecodistrict|ecoquarter]], with positive energy housing.<ref name="point2011" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.drome-hebdo.fr/.../une-nouvelle-dynamique-pour-le-port/|title=Une nouvelle dynamique pour le port}}</ref> This project could lead to the removal of family gardens there. However, there is a building plot and the gardens will be resettled on fertile lands of the plateau of Lautagne.

Like the <U+00EE>les quarter, a new quarter is planned in the south of the city on the brownfield site of the Hugo-Provence area, in place of the former Cime building (destroyed in 2013), with the construction of 200 housing units (half social, half private), shops and a hotel.<ref name="calameo" /> The first part should be delivered before 2015.<ref name="point2011" />

One of the major issues of the municipality is the opening up of the Hauts-de-Valence, which is subject to a program of [[urban renewal]] of <U+20AC>117 million, jointly funded by the city and the {{Interlanguage link|fr|Agence nationale pour la r<U+00E9>novation urbaine|Agence nationale pour la r<U+00E9>novation urbaine|National Agency for urban renewal}} (ANRU). It includes the demolition of 417 houses in the working-class districts of the Plan and Fontbarlettes and their reconstruction by the end of 2014 throughout the city.<ref name="point2011" /> The project also includes an opening up and connection of these areas to the rest of the city. Shared public spaces will be created on Roosevelt and Kennedy boulevards.

At an estimated <U+20AC>100 million cost,<ref name="point2011" /> the last big project supported by the city concerns the creation of a city of sports and culture on the former military wasteland of Latour-Maubourg. It will host the new Jean-Pommier pool, a municipal exhibition hall, a media hub with the headquarters of the radio station {{Interlanguage link|fr|France Bleu Dr<U+00F4>me Ard<U+00E8>che}} and the ''[[Le Dauphin<U+00E9> lib<U+00E9>r<U+00E9>]]'' newspaper, and finally a centre of higher education. The renovated buildings will house a students' halls, Maestris private school, nursing school and the {{Interlanguage link|fr|<U+00C9>cole sup<U+00E9>rieure d'art et design de Valence|<U+00C9>cole sup<U+00E9>rieure d'art et design de Valence|regional school of fine arts of Valence}}, which has created a public establishment of cultural co-operation with that of Grenoble. In addition to the space of the wasteland, the city will have the land released by the relocation of the prison, in 2015. It has also launched a study to establish a new [[Convention center|palais des congr<U+00E8>s]] in the area.<ref name="point2011" />

==History==
{{main|Valentinois}}

The [[demonym]] corresponding to Valence is ''Valentinois'', but {{Interlanguage link|Valentinois|Valentinois|"Valentinois"}} also designates a geographical area, and one of the old [[provinces of France]], with its capital Valence having been part of the province of [[Dauphin<U+00E9>]].

[[File:Valence-MaisonT<U+00EA>tes-facade.jpg|thumb|left|The {{Interlanguage link|fr|Maison des T<U+00EA>tes de Valence|Maison des T<U+00EA>tes de Valence|''Maison des T<U+00EA>tes''}}]]

The word ''valence'' comes from Latin ''valentia'', meaning "strength or capacity". Known in Roman times as ''Valentia Julia'', the city had been the capital of the {{Interlanguage link|fr|Segovellaunes|Segovellaunes|Segalauni}}, and the seat of a celebrated school prior to the Roman conquest. It became a colony under [[Augustus]], and was an important town of [[Viennensis Prima]] under [[Valentinian I]]. It was the seat of a [[Diocese|bishopric]] perhaps as early as the 4th century.

In the 5th century, control of Valentia passed from the Romans to the [[Alans]] and other [[barbarians]]: in 413, the [[Goths]] under [[Ataulf]] besieged and captured the brother of the usurper [[Jovinus]], [[Sebastianus]], at Valentia on behalf of the emperor [[Honorius (emperor)|Honorius]]. In 440, [[Alans]] led by [[Sambida]] were given deserted lands in Valentia by the Romans.<ref>[[Chronica Gallica of 452]], Pith. 124</ref> Three years later, [[Flavius Aetius|Aetius]] settled the [[Burgundians]] in the region, which became part of their kingdom until 534. The city then fell successively under the power of the [[Franks]], the Arabs of Spain, the sovereigns of [[Arles]], the emperors of Germany, the [[counts of Valentinois]], the [[counts of Toulouse]], as well as its own bishops, who struggled to retain the control of the city they had won in the fifth century. These bishops were often in conflict with the citizens and the counts of [[Valentinois]] and to strengthen their hands against the latter the pope in 1275 united their bishopric with that of [[Die, Dr<U+00F4>me|Die]].

The citizens put themselves under the protection of the [[Dauphin of France|dauphin]], and in 1456 had their rights and privileges confirmed by [[Louis XI of France|Louis XI]] and put on an equal footing with those of the rest of [[Dauphin<U+00E9>]], the bishops consenting to recognize the suzerainty of the dauphin. In the 16th century Valence became the centre of Protestantism for the province in 1563. The town was fortified by [[Francis I of France|King Francis I]]. It became the seat of a celebrated university in the middle of the 15th century; but the revocation of the [[Edict of Nantes]] in 1685 struck a fatal blow at its industry, commerce and population.

===Toponymy===
The conquest of [[Gaul]] by [[Julius Caesar]] made the Rh<U+00F4>ne corridor a major north-south communication axis, linking with the new Roman possessions around the [[Mediterranean Sea]]. Many settlements were founded, including ''Valentia'', a Latin name meaning ''La Vaillante'' [brave], ''La Vigoureuse'' [strong], in the territory of the {{Interlanguage link|fr|Segovellaunes}}.

The town named ''Valen<U+00E7>a'' in [[Occitan language|Occitan]], ''Val<U+00E8>n<U+00E7>o'' in literary [[Franco-Proven<U+00E7>al language|Proven<U+00E7>al]] and ''Valin<U+00E7>o'' in local Proven<U+00E7>al.

===Heraldry===
{{Blazon-arms
| img1=Blason ville fr Valence (Drome).svg
| legend1=Arms of Valence
| text=The arms of Valence are [[blazon]]ed :<br />''"[[Gules]] on a cross [[argent]] charged in heart of a tower [[Azure (heraldry)|azure]]."''<br /><br />Motto: ''Unguibus et Rostro (claws and beak).''
}}

===Antiquity===

====At the end of prehistory====
[[File:Carte allobrogie.PNG|thumb|right|Territory of the [[Allobroges]].]]
The city of [[Marseille|Massalia]], long on good terms with Rome, asked it for help against the [[Salyes]] who had ravaged its territory. The intervention of the Romans, from 125 BC, assured its safety but the war continued against the [[Allobroges]], among whom the Salyes people had found refuge. In August 121 BC, the army of [[Fabius Maximus]] crushed them at the {{Interlanguage link|fr|Battle of the Confluence|Bataille du confluent}} (implied, the [[Rh<U+00F4>ne]] and [[Is<U+00E8>re (river)|Is<U+00E8>re]]) according to [[Strabo]] (''[[Geographica]]'', IV, 1, 11).{{cn|date=May 2015}}

[[Orosius]] noted that [[Gaius Marius]], who was sent by Rome to stop the [[Cimbri]] and the [[Teutons]], had established his camp not far from the confluence of the Rh<U+00F4>ne and the Is<U+00E8>re.<ref>Orose, ''Histoires'', V, 16, 9-10</ref> The excavations on the upper part of the plateau of Lautagne ({{convert|2.5|km}} south of the centre of Valence) revealed the presence of devices of a defensive nature dating from the 1st century BC: Thus the foundation of the city could have come from a Roman military camp.{{cn|date=May 2015}}

Even under the Roman domination, the Allobroges tribe established themselves north of Is<U+00E8>re, and repeatedly rebelled against the Roman occupation. The {{Interlanguage link|fr|Battle of Solonion|Bataille de Solonion}} was the last to take place, identifiable with the modern commune of [[Soyons]] (''Solo'' by Livy, Epitome 103) in 62 BC.{{cn|date=May 2015}}

====The selection of the site====
The city of ''Valentia'' was established on a terrace on the left bank of the [[Rh<U+00F4>ne]] river, {{convert|5|km}} south of the [[confluence]] of the [[Is<U+00E8>re (river)|Is<U+00E8>re]] and {{convert|15|km}} from the [[Dr<U+00F4>me (river)|Dr<U+00F4>me]].

This geographical situation is understood by the crossing of several routes of transport and communications:

*''Valentia'' had a privileged place in north-south trade through the Rh<U+00F4>ne and at the ''[[Via Agrippa]]''.
*''Valentia'' was part of east-west routes since the different paths, which traversed the plain from the Is<U+00E8>re Valley and the Dr<U+00F4>me ({{Interlanguage link|fr|Voie des Alpes}}), converged on the city. The ''Rh<U+00F4>ne'' was crossed at Valence on a ferry, by [[Ford (crossing)|ford]] or over a bridge.

====The ancient city====
The city of Valence, as many [[Gallo-Roman culture|Gallo-Roman]] cities, received an orthonormal plan. The orientation of the urban streets network successively followed cadastres "A" inclined N, 12<U+00B0>30'E and "B", inclined N, 23<U+00B0>E, in the Valence plain.<ref name="chouquer-odiot-370"/>

We know the ''[[Decumanus Maximus|decumanus]]'' of the city thanks to the discovery of a pavement and a sewer a few metres north of the city hall. The ''[[cardo]]'' of the urban network was the ''[[Via Agrippa]]'' that crossed the city in a straight line from the southern gate of the city to the old gate and Tower of Aion, north of the city, which later became "Tourdeon" (now destroyed).{{cn|date=May 2015}}

It was along the ''Via Agrippa'' that a ''[[Forum (Roman)|forum]]'' was located, probably surrounded by a {{Interlanguage link|fr|civil basilica|Basilique civile|''civil basilica''}}, ''[[curia]]'', a ''[[Roman temple|temple]]'', etc., of which the location is unknown.{{cn|date=May 2015}}

To the south of the presumed forum site, between the ''Rue du Th<U+00E9><U+00E2>tre'' and ''Rue Vernoux'' the ruins of the ''[[thermae]]'' were discovered. This thermal water supply, and more generally that of the city of ''Valentia'', was thanks to the numerous springs in the vicinity. The site of Valence still presents a dense network of streams and canals born of the overflow of water which escapes in sources at the foot of the terraces, forming, in the east, a curved line from the source of the Treuil up to the Fountain of Malcontents, and near the Rh<U+00F4>ne and the lower town, a quasi-parallel line to the river from the Saint-Pierre source until the descent of the ''Boulevard Gambetta''. Thus, the Chony quarter (in the current commune of [[Bourg-l<U+00E8>s-Valence]]), were found remains of pipes that belonged to the aqueduct that brought water from the source of the Treuil to Valence.

[[File:Evocation de la porte Sud de Valentia.jpg|thumb|right|Evocation of the southern gateway to the city of ''Valentia'' under the early Roman Empire.]]

All around the current [[cathedral]] were discovered fragments of architecture probably belonging to a large [[temple]].

The city had entertainment facilities:

*A [[circus (building)|circus]] whose memory would be preserved in the name of the Cire quarter (<U+00AB>Siry<U+00BB> in the Middle Ages).{{cn|date=May 2015}}
*An [[amphitheatre]], was on the edge of the Rh<U+00F4>ne,{{cn|date=May 2015}} outside of the enclosure{{which|date=May 2015}} or near the New Gate.<ref name="chouquer-odiot-371"/>
*A C<U+00F4>te Sainte-Ursule [[theatre]]: Three surveys have revealed the orchestra, traces of large markets and large wall elements.{{cn|date=May 2015}} It was located at the northern edge of the city.<ref name="chouquer-odiot-371"/>
*An [[Odeon (building)|odeon]] whose curvature would be materialized by the ''Rue du Croissant''.<ref name="chouquer-odiot-371"/> In fact, the foundations of an odeon were found during the construction of the new museum, in the {{Interlanguage link|fr|Place des Ormeaux}} and its outline is materialised on the ground at the entrance to the museum.

The city was surrounded by [[Curtain wall (fortification)|ramparts]] from the early [[Roman Empire]]. This house would put in place between 15 BC and 15 AD. In 1869, excavations to the south of the old town revealed the existence of a monumental gate defended by two protruding towers. The fa<U+00E7>ade, or at least the pillars which were observed during the excavation, was covered with a large piece of sandstone and adorned with a frieze of military trophies: Shields, leggings and reastplates.

Houses settled around the city, outside the city walls.
*To the east of the city of ''Valentia'', not far from the {{Interlanguage link|fr|Voie des Alpes}} (in the direction of [[Die, Dr<U+00F4>me|Die]] and [[Gap, Hautes-Alpes|Gap]]), in the current ''Rue Faventines''.
*To the west, in the Nonniers quarter, in the commune of [[Guilherand-Granges]] (right bank of the Rh<U+00F4>ne, facing Valence): A bridge or a ferry connecting the banks of the river.

The ancient port was perhaps on the territory of the current commune of Bourg-les-Valence.

Numerous tombs were crowded at the exit of the city, along the tracks: Several burial grounds were discovered in the east and south of the ancient city.

====Late antiquity====
During the first centuries of the Christian era, Valence became an important road junction on maps and routes, and the late [[Roman Empire]], this city retained its privileged position.

However, as early as the 4th century, ''Valentia'' faced many raids but the city stayed, inside its ramparts, with its monumental adornment competing, according to [[Ammianus Marcellinus]] (''Histoires'', XV, 11, 14), with [[Arles]] and [[Vienne, Is<U+00E8>re|Vienne]].

At the dawn of the 5th century, the city lived in shelter of the ramparts erected under the late Roman Empire (still a visible construction in the 19th century). The [[Visigoths]] seized Valence in 413 AD; the [[Burgundians]] were masters of the Rh<U+00F4>ne basin at the end of the 5th century; the Valence people fell to the [[Franks|Frankish]] Kingdom in 533 AD. These successive [[Migration Period|invasions]] removed almost all traces of Romanisation.

During this troubled period, the city converted at best its ancient walls: Roman gates were bricked up, thus doing away with the two main axes of the city and lasting restructuring of the urban network. The rural inhabitants settled on small hills of the plain, giving rise to a large number of villages: [[Montoison]], [[Montmeyran]], [[Mont<U+00E9>lier]], [[Montvendre]], [[Mont<U+00E9>l<U+00E9>ger]], etc.

===Middle Ages===
[[File:Valence-PorteStRuf.jpg|thumb|right|The old gate of the {{Interlanguage link|fr|Abbaye Saint-Ruf de Valence|Abbaye Saint-Ruf de Valence|Saint-Ruf Abbey}}.]]

Around 800, a new Cathedral of Saint-Est<U+00E8>ve (of St. Stephen) was built instead of the [[baptistery]], with a [[Choir (architecture)|choir]] that was oriented to the west. It was constructed symmetrically to the Evangelist Church. It housed numerous relics: Those of saints Apollinaire, Cyprien, Corneille, F<U+00E9>lix, Fortunat, Achill<U+00E9>e and a fragment of the [[True Cross]]. The episcopal district also included housing for the canons, grouped around a court cemetery, and a round church, Notre-Dame-la-Ronde.<ref name="ed96-37">Christian Frachette, <U+00AB> Valence au dixi<U+00E8>me si<U+00E8>cle (879-1029) <U+00BB>, ''<U+00C9>tudes dr<U+00F4>moises'', no.96, d<U+00E9>cembre 1998, p.37.</ref> At the beginning of the 9th century, perhaps before, the Roman wall was raised with walls constructed from [[pebble]]s.<ref>Frachette, opcit, p.37-38.</ref> In 890, the widow of King [[Boso of Provence]] had their son, [[Louis the Blind|Louis III]], crowned King of Provence in Valence.<ref name="ed96-34">Frachette, op. cit., p.34.</ref>

In 1029, the {{Interlanguage link|fr|List of archbishops of Vienne (Is<U+00E8>re)|Liste des archev<U+00EA>ques de Vienne (Is<U+00E8>re)|Archbishop of Vienne}} invested {{interlanguage link|fr|Guigues III de Forez|Guigues III de Forez|Guigues III}} "the Old" of the County of Viennois.<ref name="ed96-34"/> It belonged to the family of the Counts of Albon, which held the region for decades, frequently occupying the county and the {{Interlanguage link|fr|List of bishops of Valence|Liste des <U+00E9>v<U+00EA>ques de Valence|Diocese of Valence}}.<ref name="ed96-35">Frachette, opcit, p.35.</ref> The region still suffered the raids of the [[Saracen]]s at the end of the 9th and the 10th century.<ref>Frachette, opcit, p.35 and 37.</ref>

The Rh<U+00F4>ne was sometimes presented as the border between the Kingdom of France and the [[Holy Roman Empire]] which made Valence part, until the 15th century, but it was especially a link between the countries bordering it. The Diocese of Valence, as the rival principality, the County of Valentinois and Diois, extended on both sides. It was also an important commercial axis, especially for salt, which would benefit the city which guards traces of the name of Rue "Sauni<U+00E8>re", formerly the name of one of the four gates of Valence, the one which gave access to the south.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.valence.fr/fr/culture/2000-ans-dhistoire/|title=Valence: 2000 ans d'histoire}}</ref> The city also benefitted from its position at a point of change in the regime of winds in the Rh<U+00F4>ne Valley: In the Middle Ages, vessels ascended the river only by being hauled to the col, by sweat (by men). North of Valence, the rise could be done under sail (but not always). At the end of the 15th century, it was even the capital of hauling along the [[towpath]], because beside this advantage due to the wind, it was a one-day stop from Lyon, and a crossroads into the mountains. Finally, the rise of the Rh<U+00F4>ne was particularly difficult at Valence, which caused forced stops. Several Valentinois were specialised in the brokerage of haulers.<ref>Rossiaud, opcit, p.290.</ref> The haulers pulled either a big boat or boat trains, with teams from a few dozen to several hundred men. Each man drew a mass of about a ton.<ref>Rossiaud, opcit, p.287.</ref> This mode of hauling regressed at the end of the 15th century, to be replaced by hauling by horses, except for local hauling.<ref>Rossiaud, opcit, p.296.</ref>

[[File:Cath<U+00E9>drale de Valence - 2014-09-28- P1940386-P1940389.jpg|thumb|left|The [[Valence Cathedral|Saint-Apollinaire Cathedral]], seen from the {{Interlanguage link|fr|Place des Ormeaux}} in {{Interlanguage link|fr|Vieux Valence}}.]]

The city, safe from the flooding of the river and protected by its ramparts, was a step on the road for pilgrimages to [[Santiago de Compostela|Compostela]]. Religious life flourished, the [[Valence Cathedral|Saint-Apollinaire Cathedral]] was built as well as the Abbey of the canons of {{Interlanguage link|fr|Abbaye Saint-Ruf de Valence|Abbaye Saint-Ruf de Valence|Saint-Ruf}}. Two major characters vied for power over the city: The Bishop and the [[Duke of Valentinois|Count of Valentinois]].

Economic growth translated into the development of towns, especially on the side of the Rh<U+00F4>ne: The Rivi<U+00E8>re (Riperia) said today, less poetically, as "Basse-Ville". The new city, north of the former Pomperi gate and Bourg-Saint-Pierre, formed around the Abbey of Saint-Pierre, which spawned the current commune of [[Bourg-l<U+00E8>s-Valence]]. Elsewhere, on the middle terrace, habitat outside-the-walls was associated with religious foundations: The commandery of the Hospitallers, the Tourdeon gate, the Abbey of Saint-F<U+00E9>lix, the Saint-Sulpice gate, the Faventines Templar Commandery, the Benedictine Priory of Saint-Victor in the south near the former ''[[Via Agrippa]]'' and, perhaps, further to the south, a [[Leper colony|leprosarium]] whose memory is retained through the channel of la Maladi<U+00E8>re.

After the disappearance of the County of {{Interlanguage link|fr|Valentinois}}, incorporated into the {{Interlanguage link|fr|Province of Dauphin<U+00E9>|Province du Dauphin<U+00E9>}}, the dauphin {{Interlanguage link|fr|Louis II de Poitiers-Valentinois}} may have imposed homage to the Bishop and Abbot of Saint-Ruf (free Abbot and immuniste): Valence was therefore incorporated into the province of Dauphin<U+00E9>. On the death of Louis II, who was the last count, the Valentinois was sold in 1419 by his heirs, his daughter Louise de Poitiers (widow of {{Interlanguage link|fr|Humbert VII de Thoire}} and Villars) and close relatives to Charles, dauphin and King of France ([[Charles VII of France|Charles VII]]). The County of Valentinois was attached to the {{Interlanguage link|fr|Crown of France|Couronne de France}} in 1424.

[[File:LL 24 - VALENCE - La Gare.jpg|thumb|right|The city was connected to the railway in 1854. [[gare de Valence-Ville|Valence-Ville Station]] is shown here with the statue of {{Interlanguage link|fr|Fran<U+00E7>ois-D<U+00E9>sir<U+00E9> Bancel|Fran<U+00E7>ois-D<U+00E9>sir<U+00E9> Bancel|Bancel}}, in the 1920s.]]

The second half of the 15th century and the beginning of the 16th century were a golden age for the medieval city, materialised by the {{Interlanguage link|fr|Maison des T<U+00EA>tes de Valence|Maison des T<U+00EA>tes de Valence|Maison des T<U+00EA>tes}} and the {{Interlanguage link|fr|Pendentif de Valence}}. Founded on 26 July 1452 by the dauphin Louis, future [[Louis XI of France|Louis XI]], the University of Valence grew quickly. Renowned professors from various countries, as [[Jacques Cujas]] forged its reputation by teaching the law, theology, medicine and arts. After his coronation, Louis XI confirmed its preference by mailing the letters patent for the university on 12 October 1461.<ref>{{cite book|url=http://books.google.fr/books?id=4-ZZAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA127|title=Ordonnances des roys de France de la troisi<U+00E8>me race}}</ref> In March 1480, the King still supported his preferred university.<ref>{{cite book|url=http://books.google.fr/books?id=j3kUAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA538|title=Lettres patentes de Louis XI, Plessis-du-Parc-l<U+00E8>z-Tours, mars 1480 (1479 avant P<U+00E2>ques)}}</ref>

The dauphin Louis made numerous stays in Valence where, as a sign of allegiance, he donated a gate to the city, the Sauni<U+00E8>re gate and a few houses nearby. It made for a "delphinal palace", later occupied by the religious order of the [[Recollects]]. As Louis XI, he allowed a market in the town of Valence, in 1476, during his stay in the city<ref>{{cite book|url=http://books.google.fr/books?id=j3kUAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA189|title=Lettres patentes de Louis XI, Valence, mars 1476 (1475 avant P<U+00E2>ques)}}</ref> and confirmed tax privileges for the city of Valence.

This era ended abruptly in 1562 during the occupation of the city by the troops of the Protestant [[Fran<U+00E7>ois de Beaumont, baron des Adrets|Baron des Adrets]]: All the religious buildings of Valence were partially or completely destroyed.

===Early Modern era===
[[File:Valence - Pont suspendu.jpg|thumb|left|The Segiun gateway (1900), built from 1827 replaced the old stone bridge, and then by the current Fr<U+00E9>d<U+00E9>ric Mistral Bridge.]]

[[Fran<U+00E7>ois Rabelais]] studied at Valence in 1532, before settling in Lyon, a great cultural centre where the library trade blossomed.

A strategic point of the Rhone Valley, Valence was a military place since its origin and had 7,100 inhabitants in the 1700s. It was to them to bear the responsibility of housing men of war and it was also to reduce this scourge that a municipal deliberation was offered, in 1714, with the construction of barracks in the current ''Rue Bouffier''.<ref name="Bonaparte et Valence">{{cite web|url=http://www.bonaparte-a-valence.fr/bonaparte_et_valence.html/|title=Bonaparte et Valence}}</ref> a A temporary camp which quickly became inadequate to accommodate 12,000 men and 20,000 Cavalry horses, the city invested 190,000 [[French livre|livres]] for the installation of new barracks in the Rollin quarter, north of the Roman road.

[[Charles IX of France|Charles IX]] passed through the town during his [[Charles IX's grand tour of France|royal tour of France]] (1564-1566), accompanied by the [[Cour de France|Court]] and the nobles of the Kingdom: His brother the [[Henry III of France|Duke of Anjou]], [[Henry IV of France|Henri de Navarre]] and the [[Charles de Bourbon (cardinal)|Cardinals of Bourbon]] and [[Charles, Cardinal of Lorraine|Lorraine]].<ref>Guerres de religion, Miquel, p.254</ref>

It was in Valence that the saga of [[Louis Mandrin]] ended in May 1755, the smuggler who challenged the [[Ferme G<U+00E9>n<U+00E9>rale]] and redistributed the proceeds of his theft from it. After spending several days in the city prison, Mandrin was [[Capital punishment|sentenced to death]]: It was conducted on the {{Interlanguage link|fr|Place des Clercs|Place des Clercs|''Place des Clercs''}} where the scaffold was erected, his death ensued on the [[breaking wheel]]. His body was exposed after his death, during three days, and many people flocked to pay him a last tribute, as his popularity increased. The death of Mandrin on the wheel of Valence marked the end of his actions, but also the beginning of a legend, as the man had marked the minds of his contemporaries.

[[Napoleon|Napoleon Bonaparte]] was assigned in the city from 1785 to 1786 in the La F<U+00E8>re [[artillery]] regiment. He made many future visits.<ref name="Bonaparte et Valence"/> He would indeed return repeatedly to Valence. It included crossing the city on 12 October 1799, during the return of the expedition to Egypt, and offered to his former landlady who came to welcome him at the posthouse, a cashmere of India (offered to the Sisters of the Blessed Sacrament), a compass and a powder spoon (available at the Museum of Valence in 1862). He also met the future Cardinal {{Interlanguage link|fr|Giuseppe Spina|Giuseppe Spina|Spina}}, who would negotiate on behalf of [[Pope Pius VII]] in the Concordat of 1801, on the same day.

===French Revolution===
[[File:Valence place Republique train vapeur.jpg|thumb|right|A steam train of Ard<U+00E8>che, in the ''Place de la R<U+00E9>publique'' (in 1910)]]

After the convening of the [[Estates-General of 1789|Estates-General]], agitation and anxiety grew until the [[storming of the Bastille]], news of which reached the region around 20 July, causing hope but also increasing concerns of a [[reactionary]] plot of aristocrats.<ref>Yoichi Uriu, <U+00AB> [http://www.persee.fr/web/revues/home/prescript/article/ahrf_0003-4436_1990_num_280_1_1320 Espace et R<U+00E9>volution : enqu<U+00EA>te, grande peur et f<U+00E9>d<U+00E9>rations] <U+00BB>, ''Annales historiques de la R<U+00E9>volution fran<U+00E7>aise''. no.280, 1990, p.154.</ref> The [[Great Fear]] arose in the region of a rumor, and spread by degrees, at a blistering pace according to local networks, putting all the villages in motion for their defence.<ref>Uriu, opcit, p.155.</ref> Once the peak of fear passed, a latent anxiety remained, the village communities realised that in an emergency, they were in fact isolated and practically reduced to their own devices.<ref>Uriu, opcit, p.156-157.</ref> [[National Guard (France)|National guards]] were formed quickly, including in Valence, but communities found it insufficient, and they constituted local federations of mutual assistance, bypassing the old provincial divisions. In the region, it was [[Largenti<U+00E8>re]] which called for a F<U+00EA>te de la F<U+00E9>d<U+00E9>ration on 23 August, [[Romans-sur-Is<U+00E8>re]] in September, [[La Voulte-sur-Rh<U+00F4>ne|La Voulte]] gathered 12,000 National Guardsmen to the ''Champs de l<U+2019><U+00C9>toile'' on 29 November.<ref>Uriu, opcit, p.157-158.</ref> Valence invited the surrounding communities on 31 January and brought together 16,000 guards of 293 communes.<ref>Uriu, opcit, p.158.</ref> The region had other celebrations of federation in the winter and spring, culminating in the [[F<U+00EA>te de la F<U+00E9>d<U+00E9>ration]] of 14 July 1790, celebrated in Paris and simultaneously in 250 cities in France, including Valence.<ref>Uriu, opcit, p.160.</ref>

The university disappeared in 1792 to be reborn at the end of the 20th century.

===20th century===

====Armenian community====
[[Image:M<U+00E9>morial de l'affiche rouge.jpg|thumb|right|Memorial of the Manouchian group of Valence]]

After the [[Armenian Genocide]] of 1915, many Armenians took refuge in France in the 1920s. In memory of the community, the first arrivals were recruited by Valence employers who went to Marseille to recruit 150 in 1922.<ref name="acam"/> There were 827 Armenians settled in Valence by 1926, and 1,670 in 1931,<ref>P. Garagnon, [http://www.persee.fr/web/revues/home/prescript/article/rga_0035-1121_1956_num_44_3_1781 La colonie arm<U+00E9>nienne de Valence-sur-Rh<U+00F4>ne], ''Revue de g<U+00E9>ographie alpine'', 1956, Tome 44, n<U+00B0>3, p.524.</ref> from [[Bursa]], [[Malatya]] and [[Elaz<U+0131><U+011F>|Harput]].<ref name="acam"/> If the Armenians were popular among their employers, they encountered the distrust of the Valence people.<ref name="acam"/><ref>Garagnon, opcit, p.538.</ref> It was a group whith a very high proportion of young adults, children and the elderly who suffered most from the genocide and the journey of exile.<ref>Garagnon, opcit, p.524-525.</ref> They were used mainly as labourers, or founded small businesses (for 25% of employees).<ref>Garagnon, opcit, p.525-526.</ref> Very quickly, an "Armenian quarter" was created, between ''Boulevard Vauban'', ''Rue Farnerie'', ''Rue Madier-Montjau'', and the ''Boulevard d'Alsace'', 40% populated by Armenians. The entire old town, with dilapidated buildings, abandoned and inexpensive, was concerned by these facilities.<ref>Garagnon, opcit, p.526 and 533.</ref>

In 1956, the group had 2,500 people, or 6% of the population of Valence, and was the fourth Armenian community in France (after those of Paris, Lyon and Marseille).<ref>Garagnon, opcit, p.523.</ref> The community's very strong identity (with newspapers, cinemas, dance halls, Armenian Sports Union) was dispersed, with the 'Armenian village' on the ''Rue de Fontlozier''.<ref>Garagnon, opcit, p.534.</ref> It showed signs of rapid integration: In 1946, half of the 2,000 Armenians of Valencia opted for French citizenship.<ref>Garagnon, opcit, p.537.</ref>

In 1947, 200 Armenians of Valence took advantage of the offer to return to the [[Soviet Union|Soviet]] countries, which proved to be a failure. The strong community welcomed new refugees, fleeing Syria (1960s) or the [[Lebanese Civil War]]. Today, 7,500 Valence people belong to this community,<ref name="acam">Krikor Amirzayan, [http://www.acam-france.org/contacts/diaspora-france/rhone.htm Valence, la ville arm<U+00E9>nienne], ''Association des communaut<U+00E9>s arm<U+00E9>niennes'', consult<U+00E9> le 16 d<U+00E9>cembre 2013.</ref> which makes the Armenian community of Valence one of the largest in France: The Armenian National Union is also based in Valence.<ref>Garagnon, opcit, p.535.</ref>

This strong presence is passed into the [[Street or road name|odonymy]]: A street and a square of the old Armenian quarter make reference (with the ''Rue d<U+2019>Arm<U+00E9>nie'' and the ''Place [[Missak Manouchian]]'') and the cultural life of the community is very active, with 28 associations, including the Evangelical Church, the Armenian courts, and the House of Armenian culture.<ref name="acam"/>

====World War II====
After the invasion of Poland by Germany, on 1 September 1939, France and the United Kingdom declared war on Germany on 3 September 1939. Germany invaded France, Belgium, Luxembourg and the Netherlands on 10 May 1940.

During [[World War II]], Valence suffered several [[Allies of World War II|allied]] aerial bombardments, intended to destroy the bridge over the Rh<U+00F4>ne. On 15 August 1944, bombs destroyed several quarters and buildings in the city, including the hospital, killing 280 people. From the era of the prefecture, there remained only the gate, which has been carefully preserved since. Four days later, on 19 August 1944, a German train loaded with [[nitroglycerin]] exploded, largely destroying the quarter of La Palla and causing 335 casualties among civilians, the military and the resistance fighters. On 2 August 1944, south of Valence, bombings of the railway depot and yard of [[Portes-l<U+00E8>s-Valence]] destroyed 51 locomotives, with 12 victims and 58 wounded among the railway workers and the population.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ajpn.org/commune-Portes-les-Valence-26252.html|title=Portes-l<U+00E8>s-Valence en 1939-1945}}</ref>

The northern part of Valence, almost completely razed to the ground, was rebuilt and today one finds many administrative buildings in this area such as the {{Interlanguage link|fr|H<U+00F4>tel de pr<U+00E9>fecture de la Dr<U+00F4>me|H<U+00F4>tel de pr<U+00E9>fecture de la Dr<U+00F4>me|Hotel of prefecture of the Dr<U+00F4>me}}, the general [[treasury]], [[social security]], the post office and the police headquarters.

Dr<U+00F4>me was one of the departments where the [[French Resistance|Resistance]] was the most active.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aeri-resistance.com/html/26.php|title=La R<U+00E9>sistance dans la Dr<U+00F4>me}}</ref> In 1943, the Resistance was organised and grew, and many Dr<U+00F4>me people were called and committed themselves to the cause. With the introduction of the [[Service du travail obligatoire|STO]], young men were required to go to work in Germany. Many of them refused this situation and went into hiding in the countryside or joined the [[Maquis (World War II)|Maquis]]. Resistance developed throughout the entire department in small units. The Dr<U+00F4>me terrain was conducive to the installation of camps. The population supported increasing resistance.

==Politics and administration==

===Municipal administration===
[[File:Valence 2006-03-03 006.jpg|thumb|left|The city hall]]
[[File:Nicolas Daragon.jpg|thumb|right|Nicolas Daragon, mayor of Valence since 2014]]

The [[city]] of Valence is a [[territorial collectivity]] administered by a [[City council (France)|municipal council]] which is the deliberative assembly of the [[Communes of France|commune]] and which aims to regulate by its deliberations the business of the municipality. The municipal council elects the [[Mayor (France)|mayor]]. As for any commune whose population is between 60,000 and 79,999 inhabitants, this council is has 49 members (mayor, 14 deputies and 34 municipal councillors) elected by direct universal suffrage for a renewable term of six years.

The current mayor of Valence is Nicolas Daragon, a member of the [[Union for a Popular Movement|UMP]] elected in 2014. The current council was elected in April 2014.

The [[Seat of local government|City Hall]] of Valence employs more than 1,700 municipal officers (permanent and non-permanent jobs) representing more than 100 trades and all exercising a public service mission, ranging from the maintenance of roads, maintenance of parks, the management of cultural and sports coaching schools, etc.

Following the [[French municipal elections, 2014|2014 municipal elections]], the composition of the [[City council (France)|municipal council]] of Valence is as follows:

