====The Valence channels====
A unique ecological and [[natural heritage]] in France, channels accompany Valence since [[Ancient Rome|Roman times]]. The name of Valence comes from three Celtic words: "val" (water), "len" (plain) and "ty" (House) and would mean "water-rich inhabited place".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.valence.fr/fr/cadre-de-vie/canaux/|title=Origine celte du nom de Valence}}</ref> At the time these rivers allowed the inhabitants to satisfy many needs and activities: Fishing, irrigation, washing, soaking, driving force for flour mills, oil, fuller and silk.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.valence.fr/fr/cadre-de-vie/canaux/|title=Les canaux de Valence}}</ref> They are now a place to walk for many inhabitants.

It is in the neighborhoods east of Valence, at the foot of a terrace, the ''terrasse du s<U+00E9>minaire'', that the channels (with a total length of {{convert|17|km}}, or {{convert|40|km}} when counting secondary irrigation channels) originate. Very quickly, the Valence people strove to channel these waters forming unhealthy marshes. In the 13th century, the regulation and the use of the channels was the privilege of the monasteries of Saint-Ruf and Saint-Victor, who decided the location of the mills.

Indeed, the water used for irrigation, drinking water and washhouses, was also a valuable source of energy for the economic development of the era. The main (''Charran'', ''Thon'', ''Moulins'' and ''Malcontents'') cross the city from east to west before joining to form the {{Interlanguage link|fr|<U+00C9>pervi<U+00E8>re (river)|<U+00C9>pervi<U+00E8>re (rivi<U+00E8>re)|Canal de l'<U+00C9>pervi<U+00E8>re}} which then flows into the [[Rh<U+00F4>ne]]. In the 19th century, the channels lost their significance and would even be a little forgotten, hidden by urbanisation, high-rise buildings and roads.

In recent years, the municipality has undertaken a development work of paths, bordered by poplars and willows, along these channels. Green routes have been signposted along the canals of ''des Malcontents'', ''de la Grande Marquise'', ''de Thibert'', '' du Charran'' and ''de Californie''. Channels which still continue to water gardens. The municipality also wants to promote gentle travel along the banks of the channels.

===Parks and green spaces===
[[File:Parc Jouvet (1).JPG|thumb|left|The {{Interlanguage link|fr|parc Jouvet|parc Jouvet|Jouvet Park}} and its fountain, on the side of the {{Interlanguage link|fr|Champ de Mars (Valence)|Champ de Mars (Valence)|Champ de Mars}}.]]

Located in the city centre between {{Interlanguage link|fr|Vieux Valence}} and the Lyc<U+00E9>e Emile Loubet, the {{Interlanguage link|fr|Champ de Mars (Valence)|Champ de Mars (Valence)|Champ de Mars}} esplanade is a large walk of {{convert|3|ha|acre}} planted with [[tilia|lime trees]], with the {{Interlanguage link|fr|Kiosque Peynet|Kiosque Peynet|Peynet kiosk}} in its centre.<ref name="ed116-26">{{cite journal|first=Louis|last=Aragon|title=Le rendez-vous de Valence|id=text annotated by Bernard-Marie Despesse|work=<U+00C9>tudes dr<U+00F4>moises|issue=116|date=October 2001|page=26}}</ref>

Under this terrace lies the city garden or {{Interlanguage link|fr|Parc Jouvet|Parc Jouvet|Jouvet Park}}. It bears the name of Th<U+00E9>odore Jouvet, a generous donor who gave, to the city of Valence, the amount required for the purchase of the land and whose statue is placed near the [[Belvedere (structure)|belvedere]] from the [[Belle <U+00C9>poque]]. This garden occupies the slopes which connect the lower town and the {{Interlanguage link|fr|Champ de Mars (Valence)|Champ de Mars (Valence)|Champ de Mars}}. It is crossed by small streams and adorned with statues. The central park, it is also one of the most important monumental and civic ensebles of Valence: The [[war memorial|monument to the dead]] of the Valence commune, obelisk-shaped, was built after [[World War I]];<ref name="ed116-27">Louis Aragon, opcit, p.27.</ref> the general [[Jean <U+00C9>tienne Championnet|Championnet]], a native son, also had his statue here, which was removed in May 1944 and hidden, to prevent it from being melted by the [[German military administration in occupied France during World War II|occupying Germany]].<ref name="ed116-27"/> The meeting of physician Gilbert Dreyfuse with [[Louis Aragon]], his contact in the [[French Resistance|Resistance]], was told by the poet after war in a small article, published in 2001.<ref name="ed116">{{cite journal|first=Louis|last=Aragon|title=Le rendez-vous de Valence|id=text annotated by Bernard-Marie Despesse|work=<U+00C9>tudes dr<U+00F4>moises|issue=116|date=October 2001|pages=26<U+2013>30}}</ref>

[[File:Chateau eau valence 2004-10-30 037.jpg|thumb|180px|The water towers by {{Interlanguage link|fr|Philolaos (sculpteur)|Philolaos (sculpteur)|Philolaos}} and water in the {{Interlanguage link|fr|parc Jean-Perdrix|parc Jean-Perdrix|Jean-Perdrix Park}}.]]

Covering an area of {{convert|26|ha|acre}}, {{Interlanguage link|fr|Parc Jean-Perdrix|Parc Jean-Perdrix|Jean-Perdrix Park}} is the largest in the city. It lies in the quarter of Fontbarlettes. The park has many trees, including 400 cedars near a natural space in the shape of an [[amphitheatre]]. This park of Valence offers a fitness trail, playgrounds for children, and a wide body of water on which is reflected the two futuristic water towers. Built between 1969 and 1971 by the Greek sculptor {{Interlanguage link|fr|Philolaos (sculptor)|Philolaos (sculpteur)|Philolaus}} at the initiative of the urban architect {{Interlanguage link|fr|Andr<U+00E9> Gomis}}, the water tower is a sculpture-architecture labelled {{Interlanguage link|fr|Label <U+00AB> Patrimoine du XXe si<U+00E8>cle <U+00BB>|Label <U+00AB> Patrimoine du XXe si<U+00E8>cle <U+00BB>|"heritage of the 20th century"}} and consists of two twisted towers, the tallest measuring {{convert|57|m}} high.

The Saint-Ruf Park is the park of the former prefecture and is located in Vieux Valence. It offers beautiful views of [[Ard<U+00E8>che]] and the [[Ch<U+00E2>teau de Crussol|ruins of Crussol]]. It connects the historic centre to the old town. It was on this hillside, which is particularly well sited for sunset, that the Free Commune of Saint-Jean planted its vineyards. At the entrance to the park is the portal of the abbatial palace of the {{Interlanguage link|fr|Abbaye Saint-Ruf de Valence|Abbaye Saint-Ruf de Valence|Abbey of Saint-Ruf}}.

Located in the quarter of Valensolles, {{Interlanguage link|fr|Parc Marcel-Paul|Parc Marcel-Paul|Marcel-Paul Park}} is a landscaped park of {{convert|3.7|ha|acre}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.books.google.fr/books?isbn=2746923718/|title=Parc Marcel-Paul de Valence}}</ref> which channels a country stream, from a natural source. It features lawns which are accessible to all, a children's playground and a space for bowling.

Not far lies the Recreation Park of l'<U+00C9>pervi<U+00E8>re. In addition to its {{Interlanguage link|fr|Port de l'<U+00C9>pervi<U+00E8>re|Port de l'<U+00C9>pervi<U+00E8>re|marina}}, this park includes a body of water of {{convert|32000|m2|sqft}}, protected by a {{convert|400|m}} long breakwater. In its leisure and relaxation area, the park contains restaurants, a campsite, a hotel, a swimming pool, a tennis court, billiards, bowling, walks, and offers river cruises.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.valence-espaces-evenements.com/|title=Parc de loisirs de l'<U+00C9>pervi<U+00E8>re de Valence}}</ref>

Public green areas of Valence total {{convert|230|ha|acre}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.valence.fr/fr/cadre-de-vie/parcs-et-jardins/|title=Parcs de Valence}}</ref> (more than 10% of the area of the commune). The city's main parks are:

*The Parc {{Interlanguage link|fr|Jean-Perdrix|Parc Jean-Perdrix|Jean-Perdrix Park}}
*{{Interlanguage link|fr|Parc Jouvet|Parc Jouvet|Jouvet Park}}
*The Benjamin-Delessert Park
*The Recreation Park of l'<U+00C9>pervi<U+00E8>re
*The {{Interlanguage link|fr|Parc Marcel-Paul|Parc Marcel-Paul|Marcel-Paul Park}}
*The Park of the Trinitaires
*The Park of the Polygone 
*Itchevan Park
*The Ch<U+00E2>teauvert Park
*Saint-Ruf Park

In 2014, the municipality of Valence has the label "flowery city" with "4 flowers" awarded by the National Council of flowery cities and villages of France to the {{Interlanguage link|fr|Concours des villes et villages fleuris|Concours des villes et villages fleuris|competition of flowery cities and villages}}.<ref name=vilfleur2014>{{cite web |url=http://www.cnvvf.fr/les_villes_et_villages_fleuris-47.html|title= Les villes et villages fleuris|work=Concours des villes et villages fleuris}}</ref>

===Gastronomy===
<div style="float:right; margin-right:20px">
<gallery perrow="5">
File:Dragees.jpg|Drag<U+00E9>es de Valence
File:Suisse biscuit.JPG|The {{Interlanguage link|fr|Suisse (biscuit)|Suisse (biscuit)|Suisse}}
</gallery>
</div>
*The {{Interlanguage link|fr|Suisse (biscuit)|Suisse (biscuit)|Suisse}}, a Valence specialty, is a [[shortcrust pastry]] biscuit shaped as a man. Sometimes improperly referred to as "Puppet", the Suisse of Valence is flavoured with [[orange blossom]], it contains powder almond and small pieces of candied orange peel. The name, shape and decoration of this biscuit are inspired by the uniform of the [[Swiss Guard#Pontifical Swiss Guard|Swiss Guards]] of [[Pope]] [[Pope Pius VI|Pius VI]] who died in Valence. The Suisse is traditionally eaten during the [[Easter]] holidays and particularly during the festival of [[Palm Sunday]].
*The Drag<U+00E9>e de Valence is a confection of praline or of chocolate coated in sugar made in the purest tradition, to celebrate the solemn events of life such as baptisms, communions and weddings. The materials used are graded and regular [[almond]]s coming mainly from France (Ferraduelle), but also of Spain (Longuette, Planeta) or Sicily (Avola). These varieties are the only ones which allow the obtainment of a very pleasing drag<U+00E9>e.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.drageepraline.com/dragees.pralines.php|title=La Drag<U+00E9>e de Valence}}</ref>
*The [[fruit]]s which are commonly found in the Valence region include [[peach]]es, [[apple]]s, [[pear]]s, [[apricot]]s, [[Common fig|fig]]s and many [[Frutti di bosco|red fruits]] such as [[cherry|cherries]], [[blackberry|blackberries]], [[Prunus cerasus|wild cherries]] or [[raspberry|raspberries]].
*The [[chef]] [[Anne-Sophie Pic]] (three stars in the [[Michelin Guide]])<ref name="pic">{{cite web|url=http://www.pic-valence.com/index.php?lang=fr|title=Anne-Sophie Pic Valence}}</ref> is a restaurateur of haute cuisine and a {{Interlanguage link|fr|Ma<U+00EE>tre restaurateur}}. A graduate of the [[ISG Business School]], she is the owner of the {{Interlanguage link|fr|gourmet restaurant|Restaurant gastronomique}} "[[Maison Pic]]" located at 285 ''Avenue Victor-Hugo'' in Valence. She is the first chef to receive three stars in the Michelin Guide.<ref name="pic"/> The Maison Pic has existed since 1889 and four personalities have succeeded there, two women and two men, all from the Pic family. Andr<U+00E9> Pic, her grandfather, gained three stars from 1934.<ref name="pic"/> her father, [[Jacques Pic]], gained three stars from 1973.<ref name="pic"/>
*Baptiste Poinot, chef of the [[flavor|Flavours]] (a star in the Michelin Guide).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.baptiste-poinot.fr/|title=Baptiste Poinot restaurateur : Chef <U+00E9>toil<U+00E9>}}</ref> The flavours are taste sensations perceived by the nose as well as by the taste buds at the time of the placing food in the mouth. Flavours, it is also the name of the star restaurant, established in January 2006 in Valence by Baptiste Poinot.
*Masashi Ijishi, chef of La Cachette (one star in the Michelin Guide).

===Garrison town===
Since installation in 1773 an artillery regiment, the [[1st Artillery Regiment (France)|Regiment of la F<U+00E8>re]], Valence was the place of confinement of numerous military units.

*The {{Interlanguage link|fr|75th Infantry Regiment (France)|75e r<U+00E9>giment d'infanterie|75th Infantry Regiment}} long occupied the Bacquet barracks
*1852-1873, a [[School of Applied Artillery (France)|school of artillery]], installed by [[Napoleon|Bonaparte]] under the [[French Consulate|Consulate]] and then abolished in 1828, since restored.
*The {{Interlanguage link|fr|6th Artillery Regiment (France)|6e r<U+00E9>giment d'artillerie (France)|6th Field Artillery Regiment}}, 1906-1914, was stationed in the Chareton barracks which was destroyed during [[World War II]].
*In 1948, the {{Interlanguage link|fr|404th Anti-Aircraft Artillery Regiment|404e r<U+00E9>giment d'artillerie anti-a<U+00E9>rienne}} moved to the La Tour-Maubourg Quarter, and then, in 1951, {{Interlanguage link|fr|477th Light Anti-Aircraft Artillery Group|477e groupe d'artillerie antia<U+00E9>rienne l<U+00E9>g<U+00E8>re}} Bacquet barracks. In 1955, the 477th GAAL was attached to the 404th RAA, which was dissolved in 1964.
*10th and 12th batteries of 155 of the {{Interlanguage link|fr|2nd Field Artillery Regiment (France)|2e r<U+00E9>giment d'artillerie (France)|2nd Field Artillery Regiment}}, 1914
*{{Interlanguage link|fr|184th Towed Heavy Artillery Regiment|184e r<U+00E9>giment d'artillerie lourde tract<U+00E9>e}}, 1939-1940
*In 1879, the {{Interlanguage link|fr|5th Cavalry Regiment (France)|5e R<U+00E9>giment de chasseurs <U+00E0> cheval|5th Cavalry Regiment}} settled in the newly built barracks, on the ''Avenue de Romans''.
*[[1st Parachute Hussar Regiment]], 1906
*{{Interlanguage link|fr|504th Tank Regiment (France)|504e r<U+00E9>giment de chars de combat|504th Tank Regiment}}, 1939-1940
:*{{Interlanguage link|fr|10th Tank Battalion (France)|10e bataillon de chars de combat|10th Tank Battalion}}
:*{{Interlanguage link|fr|11th Tank Battalion (France)|11e bataillon de chars de combat|11th Tank Battalion}}
:*{{Interlanguage link|fr|12th Tank Battalion (France)|12e bataillon de chars de combat|12th Tank Battalion}}

Since 1984, the [[1st Spahi Regiment]] has been installed at the barracks of the Bacquet Quarter.

===Personalities linked to the commune===
[[File:G<U+00E9>n<U+00E9>ral JEAN ETIENNE CHAMPIONNET.jpg|thumb|right|[[Jean <U+00C9>tienne Championnet|Championnet]], general of the armies of the Republic]]
[[File:Laurent Joubert (1529-1583).jpg|thumb|right|[[Laurent Joubert]], physician to King Henry III of Navarre.]]
[[File:Popepiusvi.jpg|thumb|right|[[Pie VI|Giannangelo Braschi]], better known under the name [[Pie VI]], he was the 250th [[pope]] of the [[Catholicism|Catholic Church]].]]
[[File:Anne-Sophie Pic sepia.jpg|thumb|right|[[Anne-Sophie Pic]], three-star [[chef]]]]
[[File:S<U+00E9>bastien Chabal.jpg|thumb|right|[[S<U+00E9>bastien Chabal]], player for the [[France national rugby union team|French national rugby union team]]]]
[[File:Mathias Malzieu.jpg|thumb|right|[[Mathias Malzieu]], singer of the rock group [[Dionysos (French band)|Dionysos]]]]

*[[Felix, Fortunatus, and Achilleus|Saint F<U+00E9>lix]], priest, sent preaching by the Bishop Saint [[Irenaeus]], with [[Saint Fortunat de Valence|Fortunatus]] and Achilleus, is regarded as the founder of the first Church of Valence, in the 2nd century. A primary school in downtown bears his name. Saint Felix and his two companions were martyred in 212 AD.
*[[Laurent Joubert]], born in 1520 in Valence and died in 1583 at [[Lombez]] (Gers), physician to King [[Henry III of France|Henry III]] of Navarre.
*[[Jacques Cujas]], Professor at the University of Valence from 1557 to 1559 and 1567 to 1575, contributed to the fame of the university.
*Marie Aymar, known as Teyssonier, and also known as {{Interlanguage link|fr|Marie de Valence}}, born in 1576, died in 1648, was a [[mysticism|mystic]], now almost forgotten, but whose fame at the time reached up to the Court of King [[Louis XIII]], making him visit in person.
*[[Balthazar Baro]], [[writer]], born in 1596 in Valence, died in 1650 in Paris. He was the first Valentinois elected to the [[Acad<U+00E9>mie Fran<U+00E7>aise]] in May 1636.
*[[Louis Mandrin]], born 11 February 1725 at [[Saint-<U+00C9>tienne-de-Saint-Geoirs]] (Is<U+00E8>re) and died in Valence, famous smuggler, nicknamed the "bandit with a big heart", sentenced to death, by [[breaking wheel]], at the {{Interlanguage link|fr|place des Clercs|place des Clercs|''Place des Clercs''}}, on 26 May 1755 before thousands of spectators.
*[[Pierre Choderlos de Laclos]] (1741-1803), the author of ''[[Les Liaisons dangereuses]]'' was first artillery officer, involved in the development of the hollow ball, charged with explosives, bursting on impact. In 1777 he received the mission to install the deemed [[1st Artillery Regiment (France)|R<U+00E9>giment de La F<U+00E8>re]] at Valence in the future barracks of the polygon. It was back in [[Besan<U+00E7>on]] in the summer 1778, perhaps inspired by his city stay, that he undertook the drafting of hiss sulphurous novel.
*[[Alexandre Camille Taponier]], general of division, born in 1749 in Valence, died in 1831 in [[Paris]]. He distinguished himself in 1789, then a mere sergeant, taking the helm of the assault during the [[storming of the Bastille]].
*{{Interlanguage link|fr|Jean-Charles Antoine Curnier}} (1751-1821), magistrate and administrator born in [[Crest, Dr<U+00F4>me|Crest]] (Dr<U+00F4>me), and died in Valence, grandfather of Jean-Charles Curnier.
*{{Interlanguage link|fr|Jean Urbain Fugi<U+00E8>re}}, born 8 February 1752 in Valence and died on 17 December 1813 at [[Avignon]], general of the Republic, he was seriously wounded during the [[French campaign in Egypt and Syria|Campaign of Egypt]] in 1799.
*The young [[Napoleon]] Bonaparte was stationed in Valence, in the [[1st Artillery Regiment (France)|R<U+00E9>giment de La F<U+00E8>re]] from 30 October 1785 to 15 September 1786, and then again from 15 June to 1 September 1791.
*[[Pope]] [[Pope Pius VI|Pius VI]] made captive by the [[French Revolution|French Republic]], taken in France, it was in Valence that he died, exhausted, on 29 August 1799, at the age of 82. It was in his honour that a pastry chef of the city had the idea to make the famous {{Interlanguage link|fr|Suisse (biscuit)|Suisse (biscuit)|Suisse de Valence}}.
*{{Interlanguage link|fr|Fran<U+00E7>ois Argod}}, born 15 May 1759 in Valence and died 27 April 1799, at the [[Battle of Cassano (1799)|Battle of Cassano]], general of the armies of the Republic.
*[[Jean <U+00C9>tienne Championnet]], born 13 April 1762 in [[Alixan]] (Dr<U+00F4>me) and died in 1800, general of the armies of the Republic. Under the command of [[Jean Baptiste Kl<U+00E9>ber|Kl<U+00E9>ber]], then [[Lazare Hoche|Hoche]], he distinguished himself at [[Fleurus]] in 1794, [[W<U+00FC>rzburg]], [[Altenkirchen]] in 1796, and was successively appointed [[Commander-in-Chief]] of the [[Army of Naples|Army of Rome]] who conquered [[Capua]] and [[Naples]] in 1798, of the [[Army of the Alps]] in 1799 of the [[Army of Italy (France)|Army of Italy]], where he became sick with typhus. Bonaparte replaced him with [[Andr<U+00E9> Mass<U+00E9>na|Mass<U+00E9>na]] shortly before he died in Antibes in January 1800. His heart, deposited in a ballot box offered by [[House of Bonaparte|Bonaparte]], is located in the {{Interlanguage link|fr|Temple Saint-Ruf|Temple Saint-Ruf|Temple of Saint-Ruf}}. His statue, made by [[Victor Sappey]], inaugurated in September 1848, stands on the Champ de Mars. It was removed from its pedestal on 5 April 1944 and buried in the courtyard of the museum until the end of the war, in order to avoid the requisition of the metal by the German occupiers.
*[[Jean-Pierre, Count of Montalivet|Jean-Pierre Bachasson]], Count of Montalivet (1766-1823), peer of France and statesman, Minister of the Interior of [[Napoleon|Napoleon I]]. His statue stands on the ''Place Montalivet''. He was elected mayor in 1795. His son, [[Marthe Camille Bachasson, Count of Montalivet|Camille Bachasson]], Count of Montalivet (1801-1880), peer of France and statesman, Minister of the Interior of [[Louis Philippe I]]. The All<U+00E9>e Camille de Montalivet was named in his honour.
*{{Interlanguage link|fr|Jean-Pierre Arbot|Jean-Pierre Arbot|Jean-Pierre, baron Arbot}}, born 8 February 1767, Valence ({{Interlanguage link|fr|Province du Dauphin<U+00E9>|Province du Dauphin<U+00E9>|Dauphine}}) died 13 April 1813 at the battle of [[Castalla]], French soldier of the 18th and 19th centuries.
*{{Interlanguage link|fr|Pierre-Andr<U+00E9>-Hercule Berlier}} (1769-1821), general of the armies of the Republic and the Empire, born in Crest and died in Valence.
*{{Interlanguage link|fr|Jean-Louis Olivier Mossel}}, born in 1770 in [[Lagrasse]] (Aude) and died in 1848 in Valence, general of the artillery of the army of the Republic and the Empire.
*{{Interlanguage link|fr|Jean-Fran<U+00E7>ois R<U+00E9>alier-Dumas}} (1788-1840), born in Valence, Member of Parliament for Dr<U+00F4>me.
*{{Interlanguage link|fr|Daniel Nicolas}}, born 20 March 1796 in [[Montelimar]] and died 15 September 1863 in Valence, Member of Parliament for Dr<U+00F4>me.
*{{Interlanguage link|fr|L<U+00E9>o de Laborde}}, born on 28 April 1805 in Valence and died 15 December 1874 in [[Avignon]], Deputy of the department of Vaucluse.
*{{Interlanguage link|fr|Charles Plan de Si<U+00E9>y<U+00E8>s}}, born in 1812 in Valence and died in 1883 in [[Fontainebleau]] (Seine-et-Marne), Member of Parliament for Dr<U+00F4>me.
*[[Jean-Joseph Farre]], born 5 May 1816 in Valence and died 24 March 1887 in [[Paris]], general and Minister of War.
*{{Interlanguage link|fr|Corneille Trumelet}}, born in 1817 in [[Reims]] and died in 1892 in Valence, military writer.
*{{Interlanguage link|fr|Jean-Charles Curnier}}, born in 1817 in Valence and died in 1863 in this same city, politician.
*[[<U+00C9>mile Augier]], born 17 September 1820 in Valence and died 25 October 1889 in [[Croissy-sur-Seine]] (Yvelines), [[poet]] and playwright.
*{{Interlanguage link|fr|Fran<U+00E7>ois-D<U+00E9>sir<U+00E9> Bancel}} (1822-1871), Member of Republican, a boulevard of the city is named after him and his statue is installed in front of the station.
*{{Interlanguage link|fr|Antoine d'Estienne de Pruni<U+00E8>res}} (1834-1923), born in Valence, former d<U+00E9>put<U+00E9> of the department of the [[Hautes-Alpes]].
*[[Louis Gallet]], born in Valence on 14 February 1835 and died 16 October 1898 in Paris, poet, [[novel]]ist and [[libretto|librettist]].
*{{Interlanguage link|fr|Casimir Genest}}, born in 1846 in [[Voiron]] (Is<U+00E8>re), died in 1918 in Valence, architect.
*The poet {{Interlanguage link|fr|Louis Le Cardonnel}}, born 22 February 1862 in Valence and died 28 May 1936 in [[Avignon]].
*{{Interlanguage link|fr|Louis Ageron}}, born in 1865 in Valence and died in 1935 in the same city, painter and French watercolourist.
*[[Jules Nadi]] (1872-1928), politician born in Valence on 19 May 1872. At the age of 26, joining the [[French Workers' Party]] of [[Jules Guesde]], he directed the literary magazine {{Interlanguage link|fr|L'<U+0152>uvre (journal)|L'<U+0152>uvre (journal)|''L'<U+0152>uvre''}} in Valence. From 1903, he became one of the most faithful followers of [[Jean Jaur<U+00E8>s]] and would be successively elected as conseiller g<U+00E9>n<U+00E9>ral in 1910, MP [[French Section of the Workers' International|SFIO]] (1914), then mayor of [[Romans-sur-Is<U+00E8>re]] in 1919. He died in [[Paris]] on 7 November 1928.
*{{Interlanguage link|fr|Edmond Ponsoye}}, Protestant theologian, born in 1880 in Valence and died in 1954 in [[Crest, Dr<U+00F4>me|Crest]]. Pastor, historian of Protestantism, the son of Isidore Ponsoye, merchant of wines in Valence and Marie Dorsival.
*{{Interlanguage link|fr|Gaston Dintrat}}, born 10 May 1889 in Valence and buried in that same city after his death on 5 July 1964 in [[La Roche-de-Glun]] (Dr<U+00F4>me), was a sculptor. He made numerous [[sculpture]]s, including ''Le Rh<U+00F4>ne'' in the basement of the wall of the {{Interlanguage link|fr|H<U+00F4>tel de pr<U+00E9>fecture de la Dr<U+00F4>me|H<U+00F4>tel de pr<U+00E9>fecture de la Dr<U+00F4>me|prefecture of the Dr<U+00F4>me}} at Valence.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.etudesdromoises.com/pages/pages_revue/resumes_d_articles/g_dintrat.htm|title=Gaston Dintrat, sculpteur|accessdate=4 May 2015}}</ref>
*[[Ren<U+00E9> Alphonse Higonnet|Ren<U+00E9> Higonnet]], born in 1902 in Valence, died in 1983 in [[Switzerland]], inventor with [[Louis Moyroud]] of the {{Interlanguage link|fr|Lumitype}}, first imagesetter.
*{{Interlanguage link|fr|Maurice Chapelan}}, born in 1906 in Valence and died in 1992 in [[Coye-la-For<U+00EA>t]] (Oise), French writer, essayist and journalist.
*[[Paul-Jacques Bonzon]], born 31 August 1908, [[Sainte-Marie-du-Mont, Is<U+00E8>re|Sainte-Marie-du-Mont]] (Is<U+00E8>re) died 24 September 1978 in Valence, writer of novels.
*{{Interlanguage link|fr|Andr<U+00E9> Deluol}}, born 27 August 1909 in Valence, grandson of {{Interlanguage link|fr|Casimir Genest}} was a sculptor and painter. The works of Andr<U+00E9> Deluol are exhibited at the [[Mus<U+00E9>e d'Art Moderne de la Ville de Paris]], the Museum of the city of Paris (or Petit Palais), and in those of Poitiers, N<U+00EE>mes, Valence, and Amsterdam. Note also the Museum Deluol de [[Saint-Michel-en-l'Herm]] (Vend<U+00E9>e) and rich with 150 works by the sculptor and painter.
*[[Paul Ric<U+0153>ur]], born 27 February 1913 in Valence and died on 20 May 2005 in [[Ch<U+00E2>tenay-Malabry]] (Hauts-de-Seine), [[philosopher]].
*[[Jean-Robert]] was born in 1921 in Valence, fantasy painter. Works by Jean-Robert are contained in the fonds of the Museum of Valence, the city of Paris, Beaubourg, and of many private collections in France and abroad. There is a permanent exhibition at the House of the Pra, in Valence.
*[[Catherine Langeais]], born 9 August 1923 in Valence and died on 23 April 1998 in [[Mantes-la-Jolie]] (Yvelines), film actress and presenter of French television.
*[[Marc Aryan|Henri Merkarian]], born 14 November 1926 in Valence and died 30 November 1985 in [[Belgium]], singer of [[Armenia]]n origin.
*[[Jacques Pic]], born 31 October 1932 in [[Saint-P<U+00E9>ray]] (Ard<U+00E8>che) and died on 19 September 1992 in Valence, master [[chef]] 3 stars in the [[Michelin Guide]] in 1973.
*The [[Abb<U+00E9> Pierre]] was ordained Deacon on Saturday, 18 December 1937, by Bishop Pic, {{Interlanguage link|fr|List of Bishops of Valence|Liste des <U+00E9>v<U+00EA>ques de Valence|Bishop of Valence}} in the chapel of the Grand S<U+00E9>minaire, 75 ''Rue Montplaisir'', which today houses the {{interlanguage link|fr|Lyc<U+00E9>e priv<U+00E9> catholique Montplaisir}}.
*[[Louis Nicollin]], born 29 June 1943, [[President|Owner]] of [[2011-12 Ligue 1|2011-12]] [[Ligue 1]] Champions [[Montpellier HSC]] and also owner of the waste collection Nicollin group.
*[[Jacques Tardi]], born 30 August 1946 in Valence, author of various [[bande dessin<U+00E9>e|bandes dessin<U+00E9>es]] including ''[[Les Aventures extraordinaires d'Ad<U+00E8>le Blanc-Sec]]''.
*{{Interlanguage link|fr|Jacques-R<U+00E9>my Girerd}}, born in 1952, writer, filmmaker, founder of [[Folimage]] (1981), president of the Court of Images, president of la Poudri<U+00E8>re, chevalier des Arts et des Lettres, chevalier of the national order of merit.
*{{Interlanguage link|fr|Catherine Fradier}}, born in 1958 in Valence, French writer of detective novels.
*[[Alain Robert]], urban climber, sometimes nicknamed ''[[Spider-Man]]'', born 7 April 1962 in [[Digoin]] (Sa<U+00F4>ne-et-Loire), grew up in Valence.
*[[Anne-Sophie Pic]], born 12 July 1969 in Valence, master [[chef]] 3 stars in the [[Michelin Guide]] of the "[[Maison Pic]]" (three times 3 stars) since 2007 in Valence.
*[[Jean-Fran<U+00E7>ois Pi<U+00E8>ge]], born 25 September 1970 in Valence, master [[chef]] 2 stars in the [[Michelin Guide]].
* [[Jean-Pascal Yao]], born 13 January 1977, footballer
*[[S<U+00E9>bastien Chabal]], born 8 December 1977 in Valence, [[rugby union|rugby union player]], [[Number eight (rugby union)|number eight]] for the [[Racing M<U+00E9>tro]] and [[France national rugby union team|France]].
*[[Bertrand Gille (handballer)|Bertrand Gille]], born 24 March 1978 in Valence, [[France national handball team|international]] French [[handball]], [[HSV Hamburg]] pivot.
*[[Guillaume Gille]], born 12 July 1976 in Valence, brother of the above mentioned French [[handball]] [[France national handball team|international]], half-back of the [[HSV Hamburg]].
*[[Florent Peyre]], born 14 May 1980 in Valence, is a French comedian and humorist. He made himself known by attending the show ''[[On n'demande qu'<U+00E0> en rire]]'' on [[France 2]] presented by [[Laurent Ruquier]].
*[[Dionysos (French band)|Dionysus]], [[rock music|rock]] band formed in Valence in 1993. It is composed by [[Mathias Malzieu]], {{Interlanguage link|fr|<U+00C9>ric Serra-Tosio}} (aka ''Rico''), {{Interlanguage link|fr|Micha<U+00EB>l Ponton}} (aka ''Miky Biky'') and {{Interlanguage link|fr|Guillaume Garidel}} (a.k.a. ''Guillermo''), who met at the Lyc<U+00E9>e Camille Vernet in Valence.

==In popular culture==

===Valence and its kiosque===
[[File:Kiosque Peyet Brassac-les-Mines.JPG|thumb|right|The kiosque Peynet of [[Brassac-les-Mines]], smaller than its {{Interlanguage link|fr|Kiosque Peynet|Kiosque Peynet|Valence counterpart}}.]]

A {{Interlanguage link|fr|List of historic monuments of Valence|Liste des monuments historiques de Valence|historical monument}} since 1982 and designed by the architect Eug<U+00E8>ne Poitoux, the {{Interlanguage link|fr|Kiosque Peynet}} is a bandstand which inspired {{Interlanguage link|fr|Raymond Peynet}} in 1942 with his famous "lovers". These "lovers" would travel the world and adorn many objects. Raymond Peynet worked on that momentum for many newspapers. After becoming famous, Peynet returned to Valence in April 1966, to baptise the kiosk which now bears his name.

The lovers of Peynet inspired the song {{Interlanguage link|fr|Le Vent (album)|Le Vent (album)|''Les amoureux des bancs publics''}} of [[Georges Brassens]]. They were broken down into stamps in 1985 in [[France]], [[Cancellation (mail)|cancelled]] by the post office of [[Saint-Valentin]] in [[Indre]], each on 14 February, in [[postcards]], [[doll]]s, in books, on medals, in statues (such as the one in [[Hiroshima]] in Japan).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.peynet.com/vf/pages/musees.php?musee=karuizawa/|title=Karuizawa - Peynet, Raymond}}</ref> Subject of relentless pursuit for thousands of collectors, the little couple is famous to the four corners of the world. Japan has two Peynet museums ([[Karuizawa, Nagano|Karuizawa]] and [[Sakut<U+014D>, Okayama|Sakuto]]), while in Hiroshima, a statue of the Lovers faces the [[Hiroshima Peace Memorial|memorial of the atomic bombing]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.brassaclesmines.fr/spip.php?article31/|title=Mus<U+00E9>e Peynet, Brassac-les-Mines}}</ref> There is also a kiosque and a museum dedicated to the artist in the small commune of [[Brassac-les-Mines]]. Isabelle Bard, the mother of Peynet, was born in [[Puy-de-D<U+00F4>me]].

===Valence in film===
The following list covers films which were fully or partially shot in Valence.

*1968: {{Interlanguage link|fr|Les Cracks|Les Cracks|''Les Cracks''}} directed by [[Alex Joff<U+00E9>]], with [[Bourvil]], [[Robert Hirsch (actor)|Robert Hirsch]], {{Interlanguage link|fr|Monique Tarb<U+00E8>s}} and {{Interlanguage link|fr|Michel de R<U+00E9>}}.
*1974: ''[[Going Places (1974 film)|Going Places]]'' directed by [[Bertrand Blier]], with [[G<U+00E9>rard Depardieu]], [[Patrick Dewaere]], [[Miou-Miou]] and [[Jeanne Moreau]].
*1992: ''[[Riens du tout]]'' directed by [[C<U+00E9>dric Klapisch]], with [[Fabrice Luchini]], Daniel Berlioux, {{Interlanguage link|fr|Marc Berman}} and {{Interlanguage link|fr|Olivier Broche}}.
*1994: ''[[Les Braqueuses]]'' directed by [[Jean-Paul Salom<U+00E9>]], with [[Catherine Jacob (actress)|Catherine Jacob]], [[Cl<U+00E9>mentine C<U+00E9>lari<U+00E9>]],  {{Interlanguage link|fr|Alexandra Kazan}} and {{Interlanguage link|fr|Nanou Garcia}}.
*1996: ''[[Les Grands Ducs]]'' directed by [[Patrice Leconte]], with [[Jean-Pierre Marielle]], [[Philippe Noiret]], [[Jean Rochefort]] and [[Michel Blanc]].
*1999: {{Interlanguage link|fr|Une femme d'ext<U+00E9>rieur|Une femme d'ext<U+00E9>rieur|''Une femme d'ext<U+00E9>rieur''}} directed by {{Interlanguage link|fr|Christophe Blanc}}, with [[Agn<U+00E8>s Jaoui]] and {{Interlanguage link|fr|Serge Riaboukine}}.
*2001: {{Interlanguage link|fr|Du c<U+00F4>t<U+00E9> des filles (film)|Du c<U+00F4>t<U+00E9> des filles (film)|''Du c<U+00F4>t<U+00E9> des filles''}} directed by Fran<U+00E7>oise Decaux-Thomele, with [[Cl<U+00E9>mentine C<U+00E9>lari<U+00E9>]], [[Sophie Guillemin]], [[Catherine Mouchet]] and [[<U+00C9>dith Scob]].
*2005: ''[[Je vous trouve tr<U+00E8>s beau]]'' directed by [[Isabelle Mergault]], with [[Michel Blanc]], [[Medeea Marinescu]] and [[Wladimir Yordanoff]].
*2008: ''[[Passe-passe]]'' directed by [[Tonie Marshall]], with [[Nathalie Baye]], [[<U+00C9>douard Baer]] and [[Guy Marchand]].
*2009: {{Interlanguage link|fr|Dans tes bras (film, 2009)|Dans tes bras (film, 2009)|''Dans tes bras''}} directed by Hubert Gillet, with [[Mich<U+00E8>le Laroque]], {{Interlanguage link|fr|Martin Loizillon}} and [[Catherine Mouchet]].
*2011: ''[[All Our Desires]]'' directed by [[Philippe Lioret]], with [[Vincent Lindon]], [[Marie Gillain]] and {{Interlanguage link|fr|Amandine Dewasmes}}.
* 2014: ''[[Three Hearts (film)|Three Hearts]]'' directed by [[Beno<U+00EE>t Jacquot]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ledauphine.com/drome/2013/09/14/un-beau-casting-en-tournage-a-valence|title=Tournage du film|work=Le Dauphin<U+00E9>|date=14 September 2013}}</ref> with [[Beno<U+00EE>t Poelvoorde]], [[Charlotte Gainsbourg]], [[Chiara Mastroianni]] and [[Catherine Deneuve]].

